# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x86-assembly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:x86-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Almost all programming languages have the ability to change the order in which statements are evaluated, and assembly is no exception.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The instruction pointer (EIP) register contains the address of the next instruction to be executed.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] To change the flow of control, the programmer must be able to modify the value of EIP.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] This is where control flow functions come in.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Performs a bit-wise logical `and` on `accumulator` and `reference` the result of which we will refer to as `commonBits` and sets the `ZF`(zero), `SF`(sign) and `PF` (parity) flags based on `commonBits`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Performs a comparison operation between `minuend` and `subtrahend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The comparison is performed by a (signed) subtraction of `subtrahend` from `minuend`, the results of which can be called `difference`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] If `subtrahend` is an immediate value it will be sign extended to the length of `minuend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The `EFLAGS` register is set in the same manner as a `sub` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Note that the GAS/AT&T syntax can be rather confusing, as for example `cmp $0, %rax` followed by `jl branch` will branch if `%rax < 0` (and not the opposite as might be expected from the order of the operands).
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The jump instructions allow the programmer to (indirectly) set the value of the EIP register.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The location passed as the argument is usually a label.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The first instruction executed after the jump is the instruction immediately following the label.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] All of the jump instructions, with the exception of `jmp`, are **conditional jumps**, meaning that program flow is diverted only if a condition is true.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] These instructions are often used after a comparison instruction (see above), but since many other instructions set flags, this order is not required.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] See chapter “X86 architecture”, § “EFLAGS register” for more information about the flags and their meaning.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address (i.e. the next instruction executed will be the one specified by `jmp`).
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if operands of previous `cmp` instruction are equal.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if operands of previous `cmp` instruction are not equal.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the `minuend` of the previous `cmp` instruction is greater than the `subtrahend` (performs signed comparison).
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the `minuend` of the of previous `cmp` instruction is greater than or equal to the `subtrahend` (performs signed comparison).
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the `minuend` of the previous `cmp` instruction is greater than the `subtrahend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `ja` is the same as `jg`, except that it performs an unsigned comparison.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] That means, the following piece of code *always* jumps (unless `rbx` is `-1`, too), because negative one is represented as all bits set in the two's complement.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Interpreting all bits set (without treating any bit as the sign) has the value 2ⁿ-1 (where n is the length of the register).
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] That is the largest unsigned value a register can hold.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the `minuend` of previous `cmp` instruction is greater than or equal to the `subtrahend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `jae` is the same as `jge`, except that it performs an unsigned comparison.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The criterion required for a `jl` is that `SF` ≠ `OF`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] It loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the criterion is met.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] So either `SF` or `OF` can be set, but not both in order to satisfy this criterion.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] In the first case `SF` will be set but not `OF` and in second case `OF` will be set but not `SF` since the overflow will reset the most significant bit to zero and thus preventing `SF` being set.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] In the first case neither `SF` nor `OF` are set, in the second case `OF` will be set and `SF` will be set since the overflow will reset the most significant bit to one and in the last case neither `SF` nor `OF` will be set.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the `minuend` of previous `cmp` instruction is lesser than or equal to the `subtrahend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] See the `jl` section for a more detailed description of the criteria.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads EIP with the specified address, if first operand of previous CMP instruction is lesser than the second.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `jb` is the same as `jl`, except that it performs an unsigned comparison.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if `minuend` of previous `cmp` instruction is lesser than or equal to the `subtrahend`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `jbe` is the same as `jle`, except that it performs an unsigned comparison.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the zero bit is set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the zero bit is not set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the sign bit is set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the sign bit is not set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the carry bit is set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the carry bit is not set from a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the overflow bit is set on a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address, if the overflow bit is not set on a previous arithmetic expression.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Loads `EIP` with the specified address if the counter register is zero.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Pushes the address of the instruction that follows the `call` call, i.e. usually the next line in your source code, onto the top of the stack, and then jumps to the specified location.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Pops the next value on the stack into `EIP`, and then pops the specified number of bytes off the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] If `val` is not supplied, the instruction will not pop any values off the stack after returning.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] The `loop` instruction decrements `ECX` and jumps to the address specified by `arg` unless decrementing `ECX` caused its value to become zero.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] These loop instructions decrement `ECX` and jump to the address specified by `arg` if their condition is satisfied (that is, a specific flag is set), unless decrementing `ECX` caused its value to become zero.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] That way, only testing for a non-zero `ECX` can be combined with testing `ZF`.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Other flags can not be tested for, say there is no `loopnc` “loop while `ECX` ≠ 0 and `CF` unset”.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `enter` creates a stack frame with the specified amount of space allocated on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] `leave` destroys the current stack frame, and restores the previous frame.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] This will set `EBP` and `ESP` to their respective value before the function prologue began therefore reversing any modification to the stack that took place during the prologue.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Execution will be resumed after processing next hardware interrupt, unless `IF` is cleared.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] This instruction doesn't do anything, but wastes (an) instruction cycle(s) in the processor.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] This instruction is often *represented* as an `xchg` operation with the operands `EAX` and `EAX` (an operation without side-effects), because there is no designated opcode for doing nothing.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] This just as a passing remark, so that you do not get confused with *disassembled* code.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Asserts #LOCK prefix on next instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/control-flow] Waits for the FPU to finish its last calculation.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Examples in this article are created using the AT&T assembly syntax used in GNU AS.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The main advantage of using this syntax is its compatibility with the GCC inline assembly syntax.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] However, this is not the only syntax that is used to represent x86 operations.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] For example, NASM uses a different syntax to represent assembly mnemonics, operands and addressing modes, as do some High-Level Assemblers.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The AT&T syntax is the standard on Unix-like systems but some assemblers use the Intel syntax, or can, like GAS itself, accept both.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] See X86 assembly language Syntax for a comparative table.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] GAS instructions generally have the form mnemonic source, destination.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This will move the hexadecimal value 5 into the register *al*.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] GAS assembly instructions are generally suffixed with the letters "b", "s", "w", "l", "q" or "t" to determine what size operand is being manipulated.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] If the suffix is not specified, and there are no memory operands for the instruction, GAS infers the operand size from the size of the destination register operand (the final operand).
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] When referencing a register, the register needs to be prefixed with a "%".
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Constant numbers need to be prefixed with a "$".
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] There are up to 4 parameters of an address operand that are presented in the syntax `segment:displacement(base register, index register, scale factor)`.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This is equivalent to `segment:[base register + displacement + index register * scale factor]` in Intel syntax.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The base, index and displacement components can be used in any combination, and every component can be omitted; omitted components are excluded from the calculation above.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This section is written as a short introduction to GAS.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] If you are using a computer with the Linux operating system, chances are you already have GAS installed on your system.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] If you are using a computer with the Windows operating system, you can install GAS and other useful programming utilities by installing Cygwin or Mingw.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The remainder of this introduction assumes you have installed GAS and know how to open a command-line interface and edit files.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Since assembly language corresponds directly to the operations a CPU performs, a carefully written assembly routine may be able to run much faster than the same routine written in a higher-level language, such as C.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] On the other hand, assembly routines typically take more effort to write than the equivalent routine in C.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Thus, a typical method for quickly writing a program that performs well is to first write the program in a high-level language (which is easier to write and debug), then rewrite selected routines in assembly language (which performs better).
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] A good first step to rewriting a C routine in assembly language is to use the C compiler to automatically generate the assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Not only does this give you an assembly file that compiles correctly, but it also ensures that the assembly routine does exactly what you intended it to.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We will now use the GNU C compiler to generate assembly code, for the purposes of examining the GAS assembly language syntax.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This should compile the C file and create an executable file called "hello_c".
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] If you get an error, make sure that the contents of "hello.c" are correct.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] and the program should print "Hello, world!" to the console.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Now that we know that "hello.c" is typed in correctly and does what we want, let's generate the equivalent 32-bit x86 assembly language.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This should create a file called "hello.s" (".s" is the file extension that the GNU system gives to assembly files).
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] On more recent 64-bit systems, the 32-bit source tree may not be included, which will cause a "bits/predefs.h fatal error"; you may replace the `-m32` gcc directive with an `-m64` directive to generate 64-bit assembly instead.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] this program should also print "Hello, world!" to the console.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Not surprisingly, it does the same thing as the compiled C file.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The lines beginning with periods, like `.file`, `.def`, or `.ascii` are assembler directives — commands that tell the assembler how to assemble the file.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The lines beginning with some text followed by a colon, like `_main:`, are labels, or named locations in the code.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The other lines are assembly instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The `.file` and `.def` directives are for debugging.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line declares the start of a section of code.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] You can name sections using this directive, which gives you fine-grained control over where in the executable the resulting machine code goes, which is useful in some cases, like for programming embedded systems.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] `.text` by itself tells the assembler that the following code goes in the default section, which is sufficient for most purposes.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This code declares a label, then places some raw ASCII text into the program, starting at the label's location.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The `\12` specifies a line-feed character, while the `\0` specifies a null character at the end of the string; C routines mark the end of strings with null characters, and since we are going to call a C string routine, we need this character here.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line tells the assembler that the label `_main` is a global label, which allows other parts of the program to see it.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] In this case, the linker needs to be able to see the `_main` label, since the startup code with which the program is linked calls `_main` as a subroutine.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line declares the `_main` label, marking the place that is called from the startup code.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] These lines save the value of EBP on the stack, then move the value of ESP into EBP, then subtract 8 from ESP.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Note that `pushl` automatically decremented ESP by the appropriate length.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The percent signs designate register names, and the dollar sign designates a literal value.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] In this case, eight bytes have been reserved on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We shall see why this space is needed later.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This code `and`s ESP with 0xFFFFFFF0, aligning the stack with the next lowest 16-byte boundary.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] An examination of Mingw's source code reveals that this may be for SIMD instructions appearing in the `_main` routine, which operate only on aligned addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Since our routine doesn't contain SIMD instructions, this line is unnecessary.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This code moves zero into EAX, then moves EAX into the memory location EBP - 4, which is in the temporary space we reserved on the stack at the beginning of the procedure.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Then it moves the memory location EBP - 4 back into EAX; clearly, this is not optimized code.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Note that the parentheses indicate a memory location, while the number in front of the parentheses indicates an offset from that memory location.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] These functions are part of the C library setup.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Since we are calling functions in the C library, we probably need these.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The exact operations they perform vary depending on the platform and the version of the GNU tools that are installed.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This code (finally!) prints our message.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] First, it moves the location of the ASCII string to the top of the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] It seems that the C compiler has optimized a sequence of `popl %eax; pushl $LC0` into a single move to the top of the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Then, it calls the `_printf` subroutine in the C library to print the message to the console.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line stores zero, our return value, in EAX.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The C calling convention is to store return values in EAX when exiting a routine.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line, typically found at the end of subroutines, frees the space saved on the stack by copying EBP into ESP, then popping the saved value of EBP back to EBP.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This line returns control to the calling procedure by popping the saved instruction pointer from the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Note that we only have to call the C library setup routines if we need to call functions in the C library, like `printf()`.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We could avoid calling these routines if we instead communicate directly with the operating system.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The disadvantage of communicating directly with the operating system is that we lose portability; our code will be locked to a specific operating system.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] For instructional purposes, though, let's look at how one might do this under Windows.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Ideally, you'd want check the return codes of "GetStdHandle" and "WriteFile" to make sure they are working correctly, but this is sufficient for our purposes.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Even though we never use the C standard library, the generated code initializes it for us.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Also, there is a lot of unnecessary stack manipulation.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We save the old EBP and reserve four bytes on the stack, since the call to WriteFile needs somewhere to store the number of characters written, which is a 4-byte value.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We push the constant value STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE (-11) to the stack and call GetStdHandle.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] We push the parameters to WriteFile and call it.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Note that the Windows calling convention is to push the parameters from right-to-left.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The load-effective-address (`lea`) instruction adds -4 to the value of EBP, giving the location we saved on the stack for the number of characters printed, which we store in EBX and then push onto the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Also note that EAX still holds the return value from the GetStdHandle call, so we just push it directly.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Here we set our program's return value and restore the values of EBP and ESP using the `leave` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] The UnixWare assembler, and probably other AT&T derived ix86 Unix assemblers, generate floating point instructions with reversed source and destination registers in certain cases.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Unfortunately, gcc and possibly many other programs use this reversed syntax, so we're stuck with it.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] results in `%st(3)` being updated to `%st - %st(3)` rather than the expected `%st(3) - %st`.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] This happens with all the non-commutative arithmetic floating point operations with two register operands where the source register is `%st` and the destination register is `%st(i)`.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] Note that even objdump -d -M intel still uses reversed opcodes, so use a different disassembler to check this.
[src:x86-assembly/gnu-assembly-syntax] See http://bugs.debian.org/372528 for more info.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The x86 architecture has 8 General-Purpose Registers (GPR), 6 Segment Registers, 1 Flags Register and an Instruction Pointer.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Used as a pointer to data (located in segment register DS, when in segmented mode).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Used in shift/rotate instructions and loops.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Used as a pointer to a destination in stream operations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Used as a pointer to a source in stream operations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Used in arithmetic operations and I/O operations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The order in which they are listed here is for a reason: it is the same order that is used in a push-to-stack operation, which will be covered later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] All registers can be accessed in 16-bit and 32-bit modes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] In 16-bit mode, the register is identified by its two-letter abbreviation from the list above.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] In 32-bit mode, this two-letter abbreviation is prefixed with an 'E' (*extended*).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] For example, 'EAX' is the accumulator register as a 32-bit value.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Similarly, in the 64-bit version, the 'E' is replaced with an 'R' (*register*), so the 64-bit version of 'EAX' is called 'RAX'.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] It is also possible to address the first four registers (AX, CX, DX and BX) in their size of 16-bit as two 8-bit halves.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The least significant byte (LSB), or low half, is identified by replacing the 'X' with an 'L'.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The most significant byte (MSB), or high half, uses an 'H' instead.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] For example, CL is the LSB of the counter register, whereas CH is its MSB.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] In total, this gives us five ways to access the accumulator, counter, data and base registers: 64-bit, 32-bit, 16-bit, 8-bit LSB, and 8-bit MSB.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The other four are accessed in only four ways: 64-bit, 32-bit, 16-bit, and 8-bit.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Most applications on most modern operating systems (like FreeBSD, Linux or Microsoft Windows) use a memory model that points nearly all segment registers to the same place (and uses paging instead), effectively disabling their use.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Typically the use of FS or GS is an exception to this rule, instead being used to point at thread-specific data.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The EFLAGS is a 32-bit register used as a collection of bits representing Boolean values to store the results of operations and the state of the processor.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The bits named 0 and 1 are reserved bits and shouldn't be modified.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The EIP register contains the address of the **next** instruction to be executed if no branching is done.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] EIP can only be read through the stack after a `call` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The x86 architecture is little-endian, meaning that multi-byte values are written least significant byte first.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] This will be seen as `0xD4 0x83 0xA5 0x1B` when doing a memory dump.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Two's complement is the standard way of representing negative integers in binary.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The sign is changed by inverting all of the bits and adding one.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] In x86 assembly language, addressing modes determine how memory operands are specified in instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Addressing modes allow the programmer to access data from memory or perform operations on operands effectively.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The x86 architecture supports various addressing modes, each offering different ways to reference memory or registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] 64-bit x86 adds 8 more general-purpose registers, named R8, R9, R10 and so on up to R15.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] As well, 64-bit x86 includes SSE2, so each 64-bit x86 CPU has at least 8 registers (named XMM0–XMM7) that are 128 bits wide, but only accessible through SSE instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] They cannot be used for quadruple-precision (128-bit) floating-point arithmetic, but they can each hold 2 double-precision or 4 single-precision floating-point values for a SIMD parallel instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] They can also be operated on as 128-bit integers or vectors of shorter integers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] If the processor supports AVX, as newer Intel and AMD desktop CPUs do, then each of these registers is actually the lower half of a 256-bit register (named YMM0–YMM7), the whole of which can be accessed with AVX instructions for further parallelization.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The stack is a Last In First Out (LIFO) data structure; data is pushed onto it and popped off of it in the reverse order.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The Stack is usually used to pass arguments to functions or procedures and also to keep track of control flow when the `call` instruction is used.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The other common use of the Stack is temporarily saving registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Real Mode is a holdover from the original Intel 8086.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] You generally won't need to know anything about it (unless you are programming for a DOS-based system or, more likely, writing a boot loader that is directly called by the BIOS).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The Intel 8086 accessed memory using 20-bit addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] But, as the processor itself was 16-bit, Intel invented an addressing scheme that provided a way of mapping a 20-bit addressing space into 16-bit words.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Today's x86 processors start in the so-called Real Mode, which is an operating mode that mimics the behavior of the 8086, with some very tiny differences, for backwards compatibility.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] In Real Mode, a segment and an offset register are used together to yield a final memory address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The value in the segment register is multiplied by 16 (shifted 4 bits to the left) and the offset is added to the result.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] This provides a usable address space of 1 MB.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] One benefit shared by Real Mode segmentation and by Protected Mode Multi-Segment Memory Model is that all addresses must be given relative to another address (this is, the segment base address).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] A program can have its own address space and completely ignore the segment registers, and thus no pointers have to be relocated to run the program.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Programs can perform *near* calls and jumps within the same segment, and data is always relative to segment base addresses (which in the Real Mode addressing scheme are computed from the values loaded in the Segment Registers).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] This is what the DOS *.COM format does; the contents of the file are loaded into memory and blindly run.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] However, due to the fact that Real Mode segments are always 64 KB long, COM files could not be larger than that (in fact, they had to fit into 65280 bytes, since DOS used the first 256 bytes of a segment for housekeeping data); for many years this wasn't a problem.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] If programming in a modern 32-bit operating system (such as Linux, Windows), you are basically programming in flat 32-bit mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Any register can be used in addressing, and it is generally more efficient to use a full 32-bit register instead of a 16-bit register part.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Additionally, segment registers are generally unused in flat mode, and using them in flat mode is not considered best practice.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] Using a 32-bit register to address memory, the program can access (almost) all of the memory in a modern computer.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] For earlier processors (with only 16-bit registers) the segmented memory model was used.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The 'CS', 'DS', and 'ES' registers are used to point to the different *chunks* of memory.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] For a small program (small model) the CS=DS=ES.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] For larger memory models, these 'segments' can point to different locations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-architecture] The term "Long Mode" refers to the 64-bit mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In x86 assembly languages, mnemonics are used to represent fundamental CPU instructions, making the code more human-readable compared to raw machine code.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Each machine code instruction is an opcode which, in assembly, is replaced with a mnemonic.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Each mnemonic corresponds to a basic operation performed by the processor, such as arithmetic calculations, data movement, or control flow decisions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Assembly languages are most commonly used in applications where performance and efficiency are critical.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] This includes real-time embedded systems, operating-system kernels, and device drivers, all of which may require direct manipulation of hardware resources.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Additionally, compilers for high-level programming languages sometimes generate assembly code as an intermediate step during the compilation process.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] This allows for optimization at the assembly level before producing the final machine code that the processor executes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Each instruction in the x86 assembly language is represented by a mnemonic which often combines with one or more operands to translate into one or more bytes known as an opcode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] For example, the NOP instruction translates to the opcode 0x90, and the HLT instruction translates to 0xF4.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] There are potential opcodes without documented mnemonics, which different processors may interpret differently.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Using such opcodes can cause a program to behave inconsistently or even generate exceptions on some processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] x86 assembly language has two primary syntax branches: *Intel syntax* and *AT&T syntax*.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Intel syntax is dominant in the DOS and Windows environments, while AT&T syntax is dominant in Unix-like systems, as Unix was originally developed at AT&T Bell Labs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Many x86 assemblers use *Intel syntax*, including FASM, MASM, NASM, TASM, and YASM.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The GNU Assembler, which originally used *AT&T syntax*, has supported both syntaxes since version 2.10 via the *`.intel_syntax`* directive.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] A quirk in the AT&T syntax for x86 is that x87 floating-point operands are reversed, an inherited bug from the original AT&T assembler.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The AT&T syntax is nearly universal across other architectures (retaining the same operand order for the `mov` instruction); it was originally designed for PDP-11 assembly and was inherited onto Unix-like systems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In contrast, the Intel syntax is specific to the x86 architecture and is the one used in the x86 platform's official documentation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The Intel 8080, which predates the x86 architecture, also uses the "destination-first" order for `mov` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In most x86 assembly languages, the reserved words consist of two parts: mnemonics that translate to opcodes, and directives (or "pseudo-ops") that access features in the assembler program beyond the simple translation of opcodes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] For a list of the former part, see x86 instruction listings.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The latter part is highly assembler-dependent, with no such thing as a standard among Intel-syntax assemblers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] AT&T-syntax assemblers share a common way of naming directives (all directives starts with a dot, like `.ascii`), and a number of basic directives such as `.ascii` and `.string` are broadly supported.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] x86 processors feature a set of registers that serve as storage for binary data and addresses during program execution.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] These registers are categorized into general-purpose registers, segment registers, the instruction pointer, the FLAGS register, and various extension registers introduced in later processor models.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] These registers have conventional roles, but usage is not strictly enforced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Programs are generally free to use them for other purposes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 registers can be used by most instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 architecture in real and virtual 8086 mode uses a process known as **segmentation** to address memory, not the **flat memory model** used in many other environments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Segmentation involves composing a memory address from two parts, a *segment* and an *offset*; the segment points to the beginning of a 64 KiB (64×210) group of addresses and the offset determines how far from this beginning address the desired address is.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In segmented addressing, two registers are required for a complete memory address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] One to hold the segment, the other to hold the offset.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In real mode/protected only, for example, if DS contains the hexadecimal number 0xDEAD and DX contains the number 0xCAFE they would together point to the memory address `0xDEAD * 0x10 + 0xCAFE == 0xEB5CE`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Therefore, the CPU can address up to 1,048,576 bytes (1 MiB) in real mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] By combining *segment* and *offset* values we find a 20-bit address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Protected mode, starting with the Intel 80286, was utilized by OS/2.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Several shortcomings, such as the inability to access the BIOS and the inability to switch back to real mode without resetting the processor, prevented widespread usage.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The 80286 was also still limited to addressing memory in 16-bit segments, meaning only 216 bytes (64 kilobytes) could be accessed at a time.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] To access the extended functionality of the 80286, the operating system would set the processor into protected mode, enabling 24-bit addressing and thus 224 bytes of memory (16 megabytes).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In protected mode, the segment selector can be broken down into three parts: a 13-bit index, a *Table Indicator* bit that determines whether the entry is in the GDT or LDT and a 2-bit *Requested Privilege Level*; see x86 memory segmentation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] When referring to an address with a segment and an offset the notation of *segment:offset* is used, so in the above example the *flat address* 0xEB5CE can be written as 0xDEAD:0xCAFE or as a segment and offset register pair; DS:DX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The Intel 80386 featured three operating modes: real mode, protected mode and virtual mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 processors support five modes of operation for x86 code, **Real Mode**, **Protected Mode**, **Long Mode**, **Virtual 86 Mode**, and **System Management Mode**, in which some instructions are available and others are not.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] These instructions are available in real mode on all x86 processors, and in 16-bit protected mode (80286 onwards), additional instructions relating to protected mode are available.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] On the 80386 and later, 32-bit instructions (including later extensions) are also available in all modes, including real mode; on these CPUs, V86 mode and 32-bit protected mode are added, with additional instructions provided in these modes to manage their features.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] SMM, with some of its own special instructions, is available on some Intel i386SL, i486 and later CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Finally, in long mode (AMD Opteron onwards), 64-bit instructions, and more registers, are also available.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The instruction set is similar in each mode but memory addressing and word size vary, requiring different programming strategies.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The processor runs in real mode immediately after power on, so an operating system kernel, or other program, must explicitly switch to another mode if it wishes to run in anything but real mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Switching modes is accomplished by modifying certain bits of the processor's control registers after some preparation, and some additional setup may be required after the switch.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] With a computer running legacy BIOS, the BIOS and the boot loader run in Real mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The 64-bit operating system kernel checks and switches the CPU into Long mode and then starts new kernel-mode threads running 64-bit code.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] With a computer running UEFI, the UEFI firmware (except CSM and legacy Option ROM), the UEFI boot loader and the UEFI operating system kernel all run in Long mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 architecture has hardware support for an execution stack mechanism.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Instructions such as `push`, `pop`, `call` and `ret` are used with the properly set up stack to pass parameters, to allocate space for local data, and to save and restore call-return points.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The `ret` *size* instruction is very useful for implementing space efficient (and fast) calling conventions where the callee is responsible for reclaiming stack space occupied by parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Instructions such as `cmp` and `test` set the flags without altering operands.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] x86 assembly language includes instructions for a stack-based floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The FPU was an optional separate coprocessor for the 8086 through the 80386, it was an on-chip option for the 80486 series, and it is a standard feature in every Intel x86 CPU since the 80486, starting with the Pentium.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The FPU instructions include addition, subtraction, negation, multiplication, division, remainder, square roots, integer truncation, fraction truncation, and scale by power of two.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The stack register to stack register format of the instructions is usually `f*op* st, st(*n*)` or `f*op* st(*n*), st`, where `st` is equivalent to `st(0)`, and `st(*n*)` is one of the 8 stack registers (`st(0)`, `st(1)`, ..., `st(7)`).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Like the integers, the first operand is both the first source operand and the destination operand.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] `fsubr` and `fdivr` should be singled out as first swapping the source operands before performing the subtraction or division.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, store and comparison instructions include instruction modes that pop the top of the stack after their operation is complete.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] So, for example, `faddp st(1), st` performs the calculation `st(1) = st(1) + st(0)`, then removes `st(0)` from the top of stack, thus making what was the result in `st(1)` the top of the stack in `st(0)`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Modern x86 CPUs contain SIMD instructions, which largely perform the same operation in parallel on many values encoded in a wide SIMD register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] So for example, `paddw mm0, mm1` performs 4 parallel 16-bit (indicated by the `w`) integer adds (indicated by the `padd`) of `mm0` values to `mm1` and stores the result in `mm0`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Streaming SIMD Extensions or SSE also includes a floating-point mode in which only the very first value of the registers is actually modified (expanded in SSE2).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Some other unusual instructions have been added including a sum of absolute differences (used for motion estimation in video compression, such as is done in MPEG) and a 16-bit multiply accumulation instruction (useful for software-based alpha-blending and digital filtering).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] SSE (since SSE3) and 3DNow! extensions include addition and subtraction instructions for treating paired floating-point values like complex numbers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] These instruction sets also include numerous fixed sub-word instructions for shuffling, inserting and extracting the values around within the registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In addition there are instructions for moving data between the integer registers and XMM (used in SSE)/FPU (used in MMX) registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 processor also includes complex addressing modes for addressing memory with an immediate offset, a register, a register with an offset, a scaled register with or without an offset, and a register with an optional offset and another scaled register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] So for example, one can encode `mov eax, [Table + ebx + esi*4]` as a single instruction which loads 32 bits of data from the address computed as `(Table + ebx + esi * 4)` offset from the `ds` selector, and stores it to the `eax` register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In general x86 processors can load and use memory matched to the size of any register it is operating on.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Most 2-operand x86 instructions, including integer ALU instructions, use a standard "addressing mode byte" often called the MOD-REG-R/M byte.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Many 32-bit x86 instructions also have a SIB addressing mode byte that follows the MOD-REG-R/M byte.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In principle, because the instruction opcode is separate from the addressing mode byte, those instructions are orthogonal because any of those opcodes can be mixed-and-matched with any addressing mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] However, the x86 instruction set is generally considered non-orthogonal because most dyadic operations cannot operate memory to memory, other opcodes have some fixed addressing mode (they have no addressing mode byte), and every register has a preferred use.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] For the load, store and scan operations, the implicit target/source/comparison register is in the `al`, `ax` or `eax` register (depending on size).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The implicit segment registers used are `ds` for `si` and `es` for `di`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The `cx` or `ecx` register is used as a decrementing counter, and the operation stops when the counter reaches zero or, for scans and comparisons, when equality or inequality is detected.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Unfortunately, over the years the performance of some of these instructions became neglected and in certain cases it is possible to get faster results by coding using more elemental instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Intel and AMD have refreshed some of the instructions though, and as of 2025 some have very respectable performance.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The stack is a region of memory and an associated *stack pointer*, which points to the last item pushed on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The stack pointer is decremented before items are added, `push`, and incremented after things are removed, `pop`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In 16-bit mode, this implicit stack pointer is addressed as SS:[SP], in 32-bit mode it is SS:[ESP], and in 64-bit mode it is [RSP].
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The stack pointer points to the last value that was stored, under the assumption that its size will match the operating mode of the processor (i.e., 16, 32, or 64 bits) to match the default width of the `push`/`pop`/`call`/`ret` instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Also included are the instructions `enter` and `leave` which reserve and remove data from the top of the stack while setting up a stack frame pointer in `bp`/`ebp`/`rbp`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] However, direct setting, or addition and subtraction to the `sp`/`esp`/`rsp` register is also supported, so the `enter`/`leave` instructions are generally unnecessary.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Other instructions for manipulating the stack include `pushfd`(32-bit) / `pushfq`(64-bit) and `popfd/popfq` for storing and retrieving the EFLAGS (32-bit) / RFLAGS (64-bit) register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Values for a SIMD load or store are assumed to be packed in adjacent positions for the SIMD register and will align them in sequential little-endian order.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Some SSE load and store instructions require 16-byte alignment to function properly.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The SIMD instruction sets also include "prefetch" instructions which perform the load but do not target any register, used for cache loading.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Most generic integer and floating-point (but no SIMD) instructions can use one parameter as a complex address as the second source parameter.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Integer instructions can also accept one memory parameter as a destination operand.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x86 assembly has an unconditional jump operation, `jmp`, which can take an immediate address, a register or an indirect address as a parameter (note that most RISC processors only support a link register or short immediate displacement for jumping).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Also supported are several conditional jumps, including `jz` (jump on zero), `jnz` (jump on non-zero), `jg` (jump on greater than, signed), `jl` (jump on less than, signed), `ja` (jump on above/greater than, unsigned), `jb` (jump on below/less than, unsigned).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] These conditional operations are based on the state of specific bits in the (E)FLAGS register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Many arithmetic and logic operations set, clear or complement these flags depending on their result.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The comparison `cmp` (compare) and `test` instructions set the flags as if they had performed a subtraction or a bitwise AND operation, respectively, without altering the values of the operands.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] There are also instructions such as `clc` (clear carry flag) and `cmc` (complement carry flag) which work on the flags directly.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Floating point comparisons are performed via `fcom` or `ficom` instructions which eventually have to be converted to integer flags.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Each jump operation has three different forms, depending on the size of the operand.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] A *short* jump uses an 8-bit signed operand, which is a relative offset from the current instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] A *near* jump is similar to a short jump but uses a 16-bit signed operand (in real or protected mode) or a 32-bit signed operand (in 32-bit protected mode only).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] A *far* jump is one that uses the full segment base:offset value as an absolute address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] There are also indirect and indexed forms of each of these.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In addition to the simple jump operations, there are the `call` (call a subroutine) and `ret` (return from subroutine) instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Before transferring control to the subroutine, `call` pushes the offset address of the instruction following the `call` onto the stack; `ret` pops this value off the stack, and jumps to it, effectively returning the flow of control to that part of the program.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In the case of a `far call`, the segment base is pushed followed by the offset; `far ret` pops the offset and then the segment base to return.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] There are also two similar instructions, `int` (interrupt), which saves the current (E)FLAGS register value on the stack, then performs a `far call`, except that instead of an address, it uses an *interrupt vector*, an index into a table of interrupt handler addresses.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Typically, the interrupt handler saves all other CPU registers it uses, unless they are used to return the result of an operation to the calling program (in software called interrupts).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The matching return from interrupt instruction is `iret`, which restores the flags after returning.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] *Soft Interrupts* of the type described above are used by some operating systems for system calls, and can also be used in debugging hard interrupt handlers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] *Hard interrupts* are triggered by external hardware events, and must preserve all register values as the state of the currently executing program is unknown.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In Protected Mode, interrupts may be set up by the OS to trigger a task switch, which will automatically save all registers of the active task.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The following examples use the so-called *Intel-syntax flavor*as used by the assemblers Microsoft MASM, NASM and many others.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] "Hello, world!" can be output with little help from an operating system.
