[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Flags are heavily used for comparisons in the x86 architecture.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] When a comparison is made between two data, the CPU sets the relevant flag or flags.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Aside, from compare instructions, there are a great many arithmetic and other instructions that set bits in the flags register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Other examples are the instructions sub, test and add and there are many more.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] Common combinations such as cmp + conditional jump are internally ‘fused’ (‘macro fusion’) into one single micro-instruction (μ-op) and are fast provided the processor can guess which way the conditional jump will go, jump vs continue.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The flags register are also used in the x86 architecture to turn on and off certain features or execution modes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The flags register can also be directly accessed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The low 8 bits of the flag register can be loaded into `ah` using the `lahf` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The entire flags register can also be moved on and off the stack using the instructions `pushfd/pushfq`, `popfd/popfq`, `int` (including `into`) and `iret`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The x87 floating point maths subsystem also has its own independent ‘flags’-type register the fp status word.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In the 1990s it was an awkward and slow procedure to access the flag bits in this register, but on modern processors there are ‘compare two floating point values’ instructions that can be used with the normal conditional jump/branch instructions directly without any intervening steps.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The instruction pointer is called `ip` in 16-bit mode, `eip` in 32-bit mode, and `rip` in 64-bit mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] The instruction pointer register points to the address of the next instruction that the processor will attempt to execute.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-assembly-language] In 64-bit mode, instructions can reference data relative to the instruction pointer, so there is less need to copy the value of the instruction pointer to another register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This article describes the **calling conventions** used when programming **x86** architecture microprocessors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This is intimately related with the assignment of sizes and formats to programming-language types.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Another closely related topic is name mangling, which determines how symbol names in the code are mapped to symbol names used by the linker.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Calling conventions, type representations, and name mangling are all part of what is known as an application binary interface (ABI).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] There are subtle differences in how various compilers implement these conventions, so it is often difficult to interface code which is compiled by different compilers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] On the other hand, conventions which are used as an API standard (such as stdcall) are very uniformly implemented.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The standard for IBM PC compatibles was defined by the Intel processors (8086, 80386) and the literal hardware IBM shipped.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Hardware extensions and all software standards (save for a BIOS calling convention) were thrown open to market competition.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] A multitude of independent software firms offered operating systems, compilers for many programming languages, and applications.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Many different calling schemes were implemented by the firms, often mutually exclusive, based on different requirements, historical practices, and programmer creativity.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] After the IBM compatible market shakeout, Microsoft operating systems and programming tools (with differing conventions) predominated, while second-tier firms like Borland and Novell, and open-source projects like GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), still maintained their own standards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Provisions for interoperability between vendors and products were eventually adopted, simplifying the problem of choosing a viable convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In these types of calling conventions, the caller cleans the arguments from the stack (resets the state of the stack just as it was before the callee function was called).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The `cdecl` (which stands for *C declaration*) is a calling convention for the programming language C and is used by many C compilers for the x86 architecture.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In cdecl, subroutine arguments are passed on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] If the return values are Integer values or memory addresses they are put into the EAX register by the callee, whereas floating point values are put in the ST0 x87 register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Registers EAX, ECX, and EDX are caller-saved, and the rest are callee-saved.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The x87 floating point registers ST0 to ST7 must be empty (popped or freed) when calling a new function, and ST1 to ST7 must be empty on exiting a function.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] ST0 must also be empty when not used for returning a value.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In the context of the language C, function arguments are pushed on the stack in the right-to-left (RTL) order, i.e. the last argument is pushed first.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The caller cleans the stack after the function call returns.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The `cdecl` calling convention is usually the default calling convention for x86 C compilers, although many compilers provide options to automatically change the calling conventions used.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] There are some variations in the interpretation of cdecl.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As a result, x86 programs compiled for different operating system platforms and/or by different compilers can be incompatible, even if they both use the "cdecl" convention and do not call out to the underlying environment.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Some compilers return simple data structures with a length of 2 registers or less in the register pair EAX:EDX and larger structures and class objects requiring special treatment by the exception handler (e.g., a defined constructor, destructor, or assignment) are returned in memory.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] To pass "in memory", the caller allocates memory and passes a pointer to it as a hidden first parameter; the callee populates the memory and returns the pointer, popping the hidden pointer when returning.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] On Unix-like systems, the standard calling convention is defined in the System V ABI.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] There are separate documents for i386, x86-64, K1OM, etc.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In Linux, GCC sets the *de facto* standard for calling conventions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Since GCC version 4.5, the stack must be aligned to a 16-byte boundary when calling a function (prior versions only required a 4-byte alignment, as per System V ABI) due to the use of SSE aligned-load instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This is similar to cdecl in that arguments are pushed right-to-left.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] However, EAX, ECX, and EDX are not preserved, and the size of the parameter list in doublewords is passed in AL.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Syscall is the standard calling convention for 32 bit OS/2 API.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The three first (leftmost) arguments are passed in EAX, EDX, and ECX and up to four floating-point arguments are passed in ST0 through ST3, although space for them is reserved in the argument list on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Registers EBP, EBX, ESI, and EDI are preserved.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Optlink is used by the IBM VisualAge compilers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In these conventions, the callee cleans up the arguments from the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Functions which use these conventions are easy to recognize in ASM code because they will unwind the stack after returning.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The x86 `ret` instruction allows an optional 16-bit parameter that specifies the number of stack bytes to release after returning to the caller.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Conventions named `fastcall` or `register` have not been standardized, and have been implemented differently, depending on the compiler vendor.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Typically register based calling conventions pass one or more arguments in registers which reduces the number of memory accesses required for the call and, thus, usually make them faster.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Based on the Borland Turbo Pascal language's calling convention, the parameters are pushed on the stack in left-to-right (LTR) order (opposite of cdecl), and the callee is responsible for removing them from the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This calling convention was common in the following 16-bit APIs: OS/2 1.x, Microsoft Windows 3.x, and Borland Delphi version 1.x.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Modern versions of the Windows API use stdcall, which still has the callee restoring the stack as in the Pascal convention, but the parameters are now pushed right to left.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The stdcall calling convention is a variation on the Pascal calling convention in which the callee is responsible for cleaning up the stack, but the parameters are pushed onto the stack in right-to-left order, as in the _cdecl calling convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Registers EAX, ECX, and EDX are designated for use within the function.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Return values are stored in the EAX register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] stdcall is the standard calling convention for the Microsoft Win32 API and for Open Watcom C++.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The Microsoft __fastcall convention passes the first two arguments that fit (evaluated left to right) into ECX and EDX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Remaining arguments are pushed onto the stack from right to left.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When the compiler compiles for IA64 or AMD64, it ignores the __fastcall keyword (or any other calling convention keyword aside from __vectorcall) and uses the Microsoft default 64-bit calling convention instead.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Other compilers like GCC and Clang provide similar "fastcall" calling conventions, although they are not necessarily compatible with each other or with Microsoft fastcall.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The first two arguments are passed in the left to right order, and the third argument is pushed on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] There is no stack cleanup, as stack cleanup is performed by the callee.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As the two arguments were passed through the registers and only one parameter was pushed in the stack, the pushed value is being cleared by the retn instruction, as int is 4 bytes in size in x86 systems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In Visual Studio 2013, Microsoft introduced the __vectorcall calling convention in response to efficiency concerns from game, graphic, video/audio, and codec developers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The scheme allows for larger vector types (float, double, __m128, __m256) to be passed in registers as opposed to on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] __vectorcall adds support for passing homogeneous vector aggregate (HVA) values, which are composite types (structs) consisting solely of up to four identical vector types, using the same six registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Once the registers have been allocated for vector type arguments, the unused registers are allocated to HVA arguments from left to right.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Resulting vector type and HVA values are returned using the first four XMM/YMM registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] For IA-32 and x64 code, __vectorcall is similar to __fastcall and the original x64 calling conventions respectively, but extends them to support passing vector arguments using SIMD registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In IA-32, the integer values are passed as usual, and the first six SIMD (XMM/YMM0-5) registers hold up to six floating-point, vector, or HVA values sequentially from left to right, regardless of actual positions caused by, e.g. an int argument appearing between them.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In x64, however, the rule from the original x64 convention still apply, so that XMM/YMM0-5 only hold floating-point, vector, or HVA arguments when they happen to be the first through the sixth.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The Clang compiler and the Intel C++ Compiler also implement vectorcall.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] vectorcall only handles the 256-bit (AVX, YMM) view of the vector registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] It does not cover the AVX-512 (ZMM) view.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Before __vectorcall, ICC has a similar convention called __regcall, where as many parameters are stuffed into the registers as possible.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Intel has a Vector Function ABI based on __regcall not implemented by clang (as of November 2025).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] It deals with vectors of ordinary types, so most parameters are passed (and the results returned) via [XYZ]MM registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] A variant of this ABI employing instead the x86_64 platform's usual System V calling convention with regard to register use is adopted by glibc's libmvec and supported by GCC, Clang, and ICC.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] On 32-bit x86, GNU has a regparm attribute that causes up to three non-variadic parameters to be passed in EAX, EDX, and ECX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] It is less of its own calling convention and more of a modification that can be applied to existing calling conventions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Clang has similar "convention modifiers" in the form of preserve_all, preserve_none, preserve_most, broadly applicable to many architectures.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] GCC supports `preserve_none` on x86 and x86-64.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Evaluating arguments from left to right, it passes three arguments via EAX, EDX, ECX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Remaining arguments are pushed onto the stack, also left to right.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] It is the default calling convention of the 32-bit compiler of Delphi, where it is known as *register*.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This calling convention is also used by Embarcadero's C++Builder, where it is called *__fastcall*.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In this compiler, Microsoft's *fastcall* can be used as *__msfastcall*.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] GCC and Clang can be made to use a similar calling convention by using `__stdcall` with the `regparm` function attribute or the `-mregparm=3` switch.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] (The stack order is inverted.) It is also possible to produce a caller clean-up variant using `cdecl` or extend this to also use SSE registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] A `cdecl`-based version is used by the Linux kernel on i386 since version 2.6.20 (released February 2007).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Watcom does not support the *__fastcall* keyword except to alias it to null.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The register calling convention may be selected by command line switch.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Up to 4 registers are assigned to arguments in the order EAX, EDX, EBX, ECX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Arguments are assigned to registers from left to right.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] If any argument cannot be assigned to a register (say it is too large) it, and all subsequent arguments, are assigned to the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Arguments assigned to the stack are pushed from right to left.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Names are mangled by adding a suffixed underscore.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The stack is cleaned up by the calling function.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Variadic functions fall back to the Watcom stack based calling convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The Watcom C/C++ compiler also uses the #pragma aux directive that allows the user to specify their own calling convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As its manual states, "Very few users are likely to need this method, but if it is needed, it can be a lifesaver".
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The first four integer parameters are passed in registers EAX, EBX, ECX and EDX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Floating point parameters are passed on the floating point stack – registers ST0, ST1, ST2, ST3, ST4, ST5 and ST6.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Structure parameters are always passed on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Added parameters are passed on the stack after registers are exhausted.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Integer values are returned in EAX, pointers in EDX and floating point types in ST0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In Delphi and Free Pascal on Microsoft Windows, the safecall calling convention encapsulates COM (Component Object Model) error handling, thus exceptions aren't leaked out to the caller, but are reported in the HRESULT return value, as required by COM/OLE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When calling a safecall function from Delphi code, Delphi also automatically checks the returned HRESULT and raises an exception if needed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The safecall calling convention is the same as the stdcall calling convention, except that exceptions are passed back to the caller in EAX as a HResult (instead of in FS:[0]), while the function result is passed by reference on the stack as though it were a final "out" parameter.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When calling a Delphi function from Delphi this calling convention will appear just like any other calling convention, because although exceptions are passed back in EAX, they are automatically converted back to proper exceptions by the caller.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When using COM objects created in other languages, the HResults will be automatically raised as exceptions, and the result for Get functions is in the result rather than a parameter.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When creating COM objects in Delphi with safecall, there is no need to worry about HResults, as exceptions can be raised as normal but will be seen as HResults in other languages.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This calling convention is used for calling C++ non-static member functions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] There are two primary versions of `thiscall` used depending on the compiler and whether or not the function uses a variable number of arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] For the GCC compiler, `thiscall` is almost identical to `cdecl`: The caller cleans the stack, and the parameters are passed in right-to-left order.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The difference is the addition of the `this` pointer, which is pushed onto the stack last, as if it were the first parameter in the function prototype.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] On the Microsoft Visual C++ compiler, the `this` pointer is passed in ECX and it is the *callee* that cleans the stack, mirroring the `stdcall` convention used in C for this compiler and in Windows API functions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When functions use a variable number of arguments, it is the caller that cleans the stack (cf.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The `thiscall` calling convention can only be explicitly specified on Microsoft Visual C++ 2005 and later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] On any other compiler *thiscall* is not a keyword.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] (However, disassemblers, such as IDA, must specify it.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Another part of a calling convention is which registers are guaranteed to retain their values after a subroutine call.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This behavior is known as register preservation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] According to the Intel ABI to which the vast majority of compilers conform, EAX, EDX, and ECX are to be free for use within a procedure or function, and need not be preserved.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As the name implies, these general-purpose registers usually hold temporary (volatile) information, that can be overwritten by any subroutine.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Therefore, it is the caller's responsibility to push each of these registers onto the stack, if it would like to restore their values after a subroutine call.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The other registers are used to hold long-lived values (non-volatile), that should be preserved across calls.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In other words, when the caller makes a procedure call, it can expect that those registers will hold the same value after the callee returns.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Thus, making it the callee's responsibility to both save (push at the start) and restore (pop accordingly) them before returning to the caller.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As in the prior case, this practice should only be done on registers that the callee changes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] x86-64 calling conventions take advantage of the added register space to pass more arguments in registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Also, the number of incompatible calling conventions has been reduced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The Microsoft x64 calling convention is followed on Windows and pre-boot UEFI (for long mode on x86-64).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The first four arguments are placed onto the registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] That means RCX, RDX, R8, and R9 (in that order) for integer, struct or pointer arguments, and XMM0, XMM1, XMM2, and XMM3 for floating-point arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Added arguments are pushed onto the stack (right to left).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Integer return values (similar to x86) are returned in RAX if 64 bits or less.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Floating-point return values are returned in XMM0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Parameters less than 64 bits long are not zero-extended; the high bits are not zeroed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Structs and unions with sizes that match integers are passed and returned as if they were integers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Otherwise, they are replaced with a pointer when used as an argument.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When a return of an oversized struct is needed, another pointer to a caller-provided space is prepended as the first argument, shifting all other arguments to the right by one place.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This pointer also becomes the return value in RAX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When compiling for the x64 architecture in a Windows context (whether using Microsoft or non-Microsoft tools), stdcall, thiscall, cdecl, and fastcall all resolve to using this convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] In the Microsoft x64 calling convention, it is the caller's responsibility to allocate 32 bytes of "shadow space" on the stack right before calling the function (regardless of the actual number of parameters used), and to pop the stack after the call.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The shadow space is used to spill RCX, RDX, R8, and R9, but must be made available to all functions, even those with fewer than four parameters.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The registers RAX, RCX, RDX, R8, R9, R10, and R11 are considered volatile (caller-saved).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The registers RBX, RBP, RDI, RSI, RSP, R12, R13, R14, and R15 are considered nonvolatile (callee-saved).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] For example, a function taking 5 integer arguments will take the first to fourth in registers, and the fifth will be pushed on top of the shadow space.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] So when the called function is entered, the stack will be composed of (in ascending order) the return address, followed by the shadow space (32 bytes) followed by the fifth parameter.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Visual Studio 2008 stores floating-point numbers in XMM6 and XMM7, in addition to XMM8 through XMM15.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The calling convention does not make use of the YMM and ZMM portions of vector registers for argument and result-passing.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The calling convention of the System V AMD64 ABI is followed on Solaris, Linux, FreeBSD, macOS, and is the de facto standard among Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The OpenVMS Calling Standard on x86-64 is based on the System V ABI with some extensions needed for backwards compatibility.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The first six integer or pointer arguments are passed in registers RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9 (R10 is used as a static chain pointer in case of nested functions), while XMM0, XMM1, XMM2, XMM3, XMM4, XMM5, XMM6 and XMM7 are used for the first floating point arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] As in the Microsoft x64 calling convention, added arguments are passed on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Integer return values up to 64 bits in size are stored in RAX while values up to 128 bit are stored in RAX and RDX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Floating-point return values are similarly stored in XMM0 and XMM1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The wider YMM and ZMM registers are used for passing and returning wider values in place of XMM when they exist.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Struct and union parameters with sizes of two (eight in case of only SSE fields) pointers or fewer that are aligned on 64-bit boundaries are decomposed into "eightbytes" and each one is classified and passed as a separate parameter, as long as there are enough registers available.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Struct and union return types with sizes of two pointers or fewer are returned in RAX and RDX (or XMM0 and XMM1).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] When an oversized struct return is needed, another pointer to a caller-provided space is prepended as the first argument, shifting all other arguments to the right by one place, and the value of this pointer is returned in RAX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] If the callee wishes to use registers RBX, RSP, RBP, and R12–R15, it must restore their original values before returning control to the caller.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] All other registers must be saved by the caller if it wishes to preserve their values.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] For leaf-node functions (functions which do not call any other function(s)), a 128-byte space is stored just beneath the stack pointer of the function.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This zone will not be overwritten by any signal or interrupt handlers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Compilers can thus use this zone to save local variables.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Compilers may omit some instructions at the starting of the function (adjustment of RSP, RBP) by using this zone.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] However, other functions may overwrite this zone.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Therefore, this zone should only be used for leaf-node functions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] `gcc` and `clang` offer the `-mno-red-zone` flag to disable red-zone optimizations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] If the callee is a variadic function, then the number of floating point arguments passed to the function in vector registers must be provided by the caller in the AL register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] The stack frame is aligned to a 16-byte boundary by default.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] If a `__m256` (AVX) type is passed on the stack, it needs to instead be 32-byte aligned; if a `__m512` (AVX512) type is passed, it needs to instead be 64-byte aligned.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Unlike the Microsoft calling convention, a shadow space is not provided; on function entry, the return address is adjacent to the seventh integer argument on the stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] This is a list of x86 calling conventions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] These are conventions primarily intended for C/C++ compilers (especially the 64-bit part below), and thus largely special cases.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-calling-conventions] Other languages may use other formats and conventions in their implementations.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The x86 instruction set refers to the set of instructions that x86-compatible microprocessors support.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The instructions are usually part of an executable program, often stored as a computer file and executed on the processor.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The x86 instruction set has been extended several times, introducing wider registers and datatypes as well as new functionality.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Below is the full 8086/8088 instruction set of Intel (81 instructions total).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] These instructions are also available in 32-bit mode, in which they operate on 32-bit registers (**eax**, **ebx**, etc.) and values instead of their 16-bit (**ax**, **bx**, etc.) counterparts.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The updated instruction set is grouped according to architecture (i186, i286, i386, i486, i586/i686) and is referred to as (32-bit) x86 and (64-bit) x86-64 (also known as AMD64).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] In the 'Notes' column, *r* means *register*, *m* means *memory address* and *imm* means *immediate* (i.e. a value).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] New instructions and instruction forms added in the Intel 80186 and 80188.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Also present in the NEC V20/V30 processors and their successors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] In 64-bit mode, the `PUSHA`, `POPA` and `BOUND` instructions are not available — the `PUSHA` and `POPA` opcodes will cause #UD, and the `BOUND` opcode (`62`) is repurposed for the EVEX prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On some processors, including some 80186 variants, using repeat-prefixes with the `BOUND` instruction will modify its operation to compare only the lower-bound.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For this reason, repeat-prefixes should be avoided for this instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The "`IIMUL`" mnemonic for the 80186 multiply-immediate instruction is sometimes used in IBM PC documentation, but is not commonly used otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `REP` (`F3`) prefix can be used with the `INSB`/`INSW`/`OUTSB`/`OUTSW` instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Doing so will cause the instruction to be repeated the number of times specified in rCX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On 80286 and later processors, the `INSB`/`INSW` instructions may perform access-rights checks for its memory store after the read from the I/O port has been performed - if any of these checks fail (e.g. segfault or page-fault), then the data item read from the I/O port is lost.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For this reason, using the `INSB`/`INSW` instructions to read an I/O port that has side-effects upon read is not recommended.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] I/O port access is only allowed when CPL≤IOPL, or (on 80386 and later) the I/O port permission bitmap bits for the port to access are all set to 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For the ROL/ROR/RCL/RCR/SHL/SHR/SAR instructions, opcode `C0` is used for byte variants and opcode `C1` is used for word variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On 80186 and later, sub-opcode /6 for the shift-opcodes `C0`/`C1`/`D0`/`D1`/`D2`/`D3` acts as an (often poorly documented) alias of sub-opcode /4 — these are all variants of the `SHL` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The first argument to the `ENTER` instruction is always a 16-bit unsigned immediate regardless of OperandSize.The second argument to `ENTER` is an 8-bit immediate - on 80186/80188 and NEC V-series processors, all 8 bits are used, but 80286 and later processors use only the bottom 5 bits.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On newer processors, the `ENTER` instruction will, after setting up the stack frame, check whether the byte location pointed to by the new value of SS:rSP is writable — if it isn't, then it will generate the same exception (e.g. page-fault) as a write to that address would have caused.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The new instructions added in 80286 add support for x86 protected mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Some but not all of the instructions are available in real mode as well.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `LGDT`, `LIDT`, `LLDT` and `LTR` instructions are serializing on Pentium and later processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `LMSW` instruction is serializing on Intel processors from Pentium onwards, but not on AMD processors.When the `LMSW` instruction is used to enter Protected mode, it should be immediately followed by a jump instruction to clear the prefetch queue.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On 80386 and later, the "Machine Status Word" is the same as the CR0 control register – however, the `LMSW` instruction can only modify the bottom 4 bits of this register and cannot clear bit 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The inability to clear bit 0 means that `LMSW` can be used to enter but not leave x86 Protected Mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On 80286, it is not possible to leave Protected Mode at all (neither with `LMSW` nor with `LOADALL`) without a CPU reset – on 80386 and later, it is possible to leave Protected Mode, but this requires the use of the 80386-and-later `MOV` to `CR0` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] If `CR4.UMIP=1` is set, then the `SGDT`, `SIDT`, `SLDT`, `SMSW` and `STR` instructions can only run in Ring 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] These instructions were unprivileged on all x86 CPUs from 80286 onwards until the introduction of UMIP in 2017.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] This has been a significant security problem for software-based virtualization, since it enables these instructions to be used by a VM guest to detect that it is running inside a VM.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `SMSW`, `SLDT` and `STR` instructions always use an operand size of 16 bits when used with a memory argument.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] With a register argument on 80386 or later processors, wider destination operand sizes are available and behave as follows: `SMSW`: Stores full CR0 in 64-bit mode on x86-64 CPUs, undefined otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `SLDT`: Zero-extends 16-bit argument on Pentium Pro and later processors, undefined on earlier processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On processors with x86-64, the `ARPL` instruction is not available in 64-bit mode – the `63 /r` opcode has been reassigned to the 64-bit-mode-only `MOVSXD` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `ARPL` instruction causes #UD in Real mode and Virtual 8086 Mode – Windows 95 and OS/2 2.x are known to make extensive use of this #UD to use the `63` opcode as a one-byte breakpoint to transition from Virtual 8086 mode to kernel mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Bits 19:16 of this mask are documented as "undefined" on Intel CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On AMD CPUs, the mask is documented as `0x00FFFF00`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For the `LAR` and `LSL` instructions, if the specified segment descriptor could not be loaded, then the instruction's destination register is left unmodified.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On some Intel CPU/microcode combinations from 2019 onwards, as well as some AMD CPU/microcode combinations from 2025 onwards, the `VERW` instruction also flushes various microarchitectural data buffers in an implementation-specific manner.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] This enables it to be used as part of workarounds for security vulnerabilities such as Microarchitectural Data Sampling and Transient Scheduler Attacks.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Some of the microarchitectural buffer-flushing functions that have been added to `VERW` may require the instruction to be executed with a memory operand.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The 80386 added support for 32-bit operation to the x86 instruction set.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] (Instruction forms that work on 8-bit data continue to be 8-bit regardless of OperandSize.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The default OperandSize and AddressSize to use for each instruction is given by the D bit of the segment descriptor of the current code segment - `D=0` makes both 16-bit, `D=1` makes both 32-bit.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The 80386 also introduced the two new segment registers `FS` and `GS` as well as the x86 control, debug and test registers.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For instruction forms where the operand size can be inferred from the instruction's arguments (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `ADD EAX,EBX` can be inferred to have a 32-bit OperandSize due to its use of EAX as an argument), new instruction mnemonics are not needed and not provided.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The 32-bit string instructions accept repeat-prefixes in the same way as older 8/16-bit string instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `LODSD`, `STOSD`, `MOVSD`, `INSD` and `OUTSD`, the `REP` prefix (`F3`) will repeat the instruction the number of times specified in rCX (CX or ECX, decided by AddressSize), decrementing rCX for each iteration (with rCX=0 resulting in no-op and proceeding to the next instruction).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `CMPSD` and `SCASD`, the `REPE` (`F3`) and `REPNE` (`F2`) prefixes are available, which will repeat the instruction, decrementing rCX for each iteration, but only as long as the flag condition (ZF=1 for `REPE`, ZF=0 for `REPNE`) holds true AND rCX ≠ 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For the `INSB/W/D` instructions, the memory access rights for the `ES:[rDI]` memory address might not be checked until after the port access has been performed – if this check fails (e.g. page fault or other memory exception), then the data item read from the port is lost.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] As such, it is not recommended to use this instruction to access an I/O port that performs any kind of side effect upon read.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] I/O port access is only allowed when CPL≤IOPL or the I/O port permission bitmap bits for the port to access are all set to 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `CWDE` instruction differs from the older `CWD` instruction in that `CWD` would sign-extend the 16-bit value in AX into a 32-bit value in the DX:AX register pair.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For the `E3` opcode (`JCXZ`/`JECXZ`), the choice of whether the instruction will use `CX` or `ECX` for its comparison (and consequently which mnemonic to use) is based on the AddressSize, not OperandSize.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] (OperandSize instead controls whether the jump destination should be truncated to 16 bits or not).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] This also applies to the loop instructions `LOOP`,`LOOPE`,`LOOPNE` (opcodes `E0`,`E1`,`E2`), however, unlike `JCXZ`/`JECXZ`, these instructions have not been given new mnemonics for their ECX-using variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `PUSHA(D)`, the value of SP/ESP pushed onto the stack is the value it had just before the `PUSHA(D)` instruction started executing.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `POPA`/`POPAD`, the stack item corresponding to SP/ESP is popped off the stack (performing a memory read), but not placed into SP/ESP.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `PUSHFD` and `POPFD` instructions will cause a #GP exception if executed in virtual 8086 mode if IOPL is not 3.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `PUSHF`, `POPF`, `IRET` and `IRETD` instructions will cause a #GP exception if executed in Virtual-8086 mode if IOPL is not 3 and VME is not enabled.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] This has necessitated complex workarounds on both Linux ("ESPFIX") and Windows.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] This issue also affects the later 64-bit `IRETQ` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `BTS`, `BTC` and `BTR` instructions accept the `LOCK` (`F0`) prefix when used with a memory argument – this results in the instruction executing atomically.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] If the `F3` prefix is used with the `0F BC /r` opcode, then the instruction will execute as `TZCNT` on systems that support the BMI1 extension.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `TZCNT` differs from `BSF` in that `TZCNT` but not `BSR` is defined to return operand size if the source operand is zero – for other source operand values, they produce the same result (except for flags).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `BSF` and `BSR` set the EFLAGS.ZF flag to 1 if the source argument was all-0s and 0 otherwise.If the source argument was all-0s, then the destination register is left unchanged on AMD processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] It is usually left unchanged on Intel processors as well, but some exceptions exist: On some older Intel 64 processors, the 32-bit forms of the `BSF`/`BSR` instructions will, with an all-0s source, leave the bottom 32 bits of the destination register unchanged but clear the top 32 bits.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On 386/486 processors, `BSF`/`BSR` with an all-0s source are documented as returning an undefined value into the destination register — most 386/486 versions leave the destination register unchanged, but some early Intel 486 versions are known to modify it.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] If the `F3` prefix is used with the `0F BD /r` opcode, then the instruction will execute as `LZCNT` on systems that support the ABM or LZCNT extensions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `LZCNT` produces a different result from `BSR` for most input values.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `SHLD` and `SHRD`, the shift-amount is masked – the bottom 5 bits are used for 16/32-bit operand size and 6 bits for 64-bit operand size.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `SHLD` and `SHRD` with 16-bit arguments and a shift-amount greater than 16 produce undefined results.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `SETcc`, while the opcode is commonly specified as /0 – implying that bits 5:3 of the instruction's ModR/M byte should be 000 – modern x86 processors (Pentium and later) ignore bits 5:3 and will execute the instruction as `SETcc` regardless of the contents of these bits.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `LFS`, `LGS` and `LSS`, the size of the offset part of the far pointer is given by operand size – the size of the segment part is always 16 bits.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] In 64-bit mode, using the `REX.W` prefix with these instructions will cause them to load a far pointer with a 64-bit offset on Intel but not AMD processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `MOV` to/from the `CRx`, `DRx` and `TRx` registers, the reg part of the ModR/M byte is used to indicate `CRx/DRx/TRx` register and r/m part the general-register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Uniquely for the `MOV CRx/DRx/TRx` opcodes, the top two bits of the ModR/M byte is ignored – these opcodes are decoded and executed as if the top two bits of the ModR/M byte are `11b`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For moves to/from the `CRx` and `DRx` registers, the operand size is always 64 bits in 64-bit mode and 32 bits otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Flushing pages belonging to other PCIDs can instead be done by toggling the CR4.PGE bit, clearing the CR4.PCIDE bit, or using the `INVPCID` instruction.In 64-bit mode, TLB flushing can be suppressed by setting bit 63 of the value written to `CR3` to 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On processors prior to Pentium, moves to `CR0` would not serialize the instruction stream – for this reason, it is usually required to perform a jump (`JMP` or `CALL`) immediately after a `MOV` to `CR0` if such a `MOV` is used to enable/disable protected mode and/or memory paging.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `MOV TRx` instructions were discontinued from Pentium onwards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `INT1`/`ICEBP` (`F1`) instruction is present on all known Intel x86 processors from the 80386 onwards, but only fully documented for Intel processors from the May 2018 release of the Intel SDM (rev 067) onwards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Before this release, mention of the instruction in Intel material was sporadic, e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For AMD processors, the instruction has been documented since 2002.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The UMOV instruction is present on 386 and 486 processors only.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `XBTS` and `IBTS` instructions were discontinued with the B1 stepping of 80386.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] They have been used by software mainly for detection of the buggy B0 stepping of the 80386.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Microsoft Windows (v2.01 and later) will attempt to run the `XBTS` instruction as part of its CPU detection if `CPUID` is not present, and will refuse to boot if `XBTS` is found to be working.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] For `XBTS` and `IBTS`, the r/m argument represents the data to extract/insert a bitfield from/to, the reg argument the bitfield to be inserted/extracted, AX/EAX a bit-offset and CL a bitfield length.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On Intel 80486 stepping A, the `CMPXCHG` instruction uses a different encoding - `0F A6 /r` for 8-bit variant, `0F A7 /r` for 16/32-bit variant.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `0F B0/B1` encodings are used on 80486 stepping B and later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `CMPXCHG` instruction sets `EFLAGS` in the same way as a `CMP` instruction that uses the accumulator (AL/AX/EAX/RAX) as its first argument would do.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `INVLPG` executes as no-operation if the m8 argument is invalid (e.g. unmapped page or non-canonical address).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] `INVLPG` can be used to invalidate TLB entries for individual global pages.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] If the `F3` prefix is used with the `0F 09` opcode, then the instruction will execute as `WBNOINVD` on processors that support the WBNOINVD extension – this will not invalidate the cache.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `INVD` and `WBINVD` instructions will invalidate all cache lines in the CPU's L1 caches.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] It is implementation-defined whether they will invalidate the content of L2/L3 caches as well.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `INVD` and `WBINVD` instructions will not prevent cache prefetching from taking place while they're operating — if there is a need to guarantee that caches are empty, then it is necessary to set `CR0.CD` to 1 before invoking either of these instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] The `INVD` and `WBINVD` instructions are serializing – on some processors, they may block interrupts until completion as well.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On processors that support Intel TDX, if the SEAM (SEcure Arbitration Mode) has been set up, `INVD` will cause #GP(0).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] On some newer Intel processors (Meteor Lake/Arrow Lake and later), trying to execute `INVD` when bit 0 of the `MSR_BIOS_DONE` MSR is set will result in #GP(0) — this effectively prevents all non-BIOS use of this instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Under Intel VT-x virtualization, the `INVD` instruction will cause a mandatory #VMEXIT.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p01] Integer/system instructions that were not present in the basic 80486 instruction set, but were added in various x86 processors prior to the introduction of SSE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] In 64-bit mode, the `RDMSR`, `RDTSC` and `RDPMC` instructions will set the top 32 bits of RDX and RAX to zero.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For some CPU/MSR combinations, the `RDMSR` and `WRMSR` instructions may make use of registers other than ECX and EDX:EAX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Known examples of this include the use of EDI and ESI for a password, and EBX for a physical memory address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] MSR reads done with the `RDMSR` and `RDMSRLIST` instructions can, in general, be reordered with respect to other instructions, including other MSR reads — with the following restrictions: MSR accesses cannot be reordered across serializing instructions (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `CPUID`,`IRET`) or dispatch-serializing instructions (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] MSR reads of the `IA32_BARRIER` MSR (MSR `2Fh`, introduced with the MSRLIST instruction set extension) cannot be reordered across other MSR reads.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Accesses to the x2APIC MSRs cannot be reordered with respect to each other.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On Intel, AMD and VIA CPUs, the `WRMSR` instruction is also used to update the CPU microcode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] This is done by writing the virtual address of the new microcode to upload to MSR `79h` on Intel and VIA CPUs and MSR `C001_0020h` on AMD CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] System Management Mode and the `RSM` instruction were made available on non-SL variants of the Intel 486 only after the initial release of the Intel Pentium in 1993.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On some older 32-bit processors, executing `CPUID` with a leaf index (EAX) greater than 0 may leave EBX and ECX unmodified, keeping their old values.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For this reason, it is recommended to zero out EBX and ECX before executing `CPUID`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Processors noted to exhibit this behavior include Cyrix MII and IDT WinChip 2.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] In 64-bit mode, `CPUID` will set the top 32 bits of RAX, RBX, RCX and RDX to zero.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On some Intel processors starting from Ivy Bridge, there exists MSRs that can be used to restrict `CPUID` to ring 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Such MSRs are documented for at least Ivy Bridge and Denverton.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The ability to restrict `CPUID` to ring 0 also exists on AMD processors supporting the "CpuidUserDis" feature (Zen 4 "Raphael" and later).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `CPUID` is also available on some Intel and AMD 486 processor variants that were released after the initial release of the Intel Pentium.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On the Cyrix 5x86 and 6x86 CPUs, `CPUID` is not enabled by default and must be enabled through a Cyrix configuration register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On NexGen CPUs, `CPUID` is only supported with some system BIOSes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On some NexGen CPUs that do support `CPUID`, EFLAGS.ID is not supported but EFLAGS.AC is, complicating CPU detection.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Unlike the older `CMPXCHG` instruction, the `CMPXCHG8B` instruction does not modify any EFLAGS bits other than ZF.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `LOCK CMPXCHG8B` with a register operand (which is an invalid encoding) will, on some Intel Pentium CPUs, cause a hang rather than the expected #UD exception - this is known as the Pentium F00F bug.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On IDT WinChip, Transmeta Crusoe and Rise mP6 processors, the `CMPXCHG8B` instruction is always supported, however its CPUID bit may be missing.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] This is a workaround for a bug in Windows NT.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `RDTSC` and `RDPMC` instructions are not ordered with respect to other instructions, and may sample their respective counters before earlier instructions are executed or after later instructions have executed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Invocations of `RDPMC` (but not `RDTSC`) may be reordered relative to each other even for reads of the same counter.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] In order to impose ordering with respect to other instructions, `LFENCE` or serializing instructions (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On all x86 processors that support both `RDTSC` and MSRs, the TSC is available as MSR `10h`, which can be read and written using the `RDMSR`/`WRMSR` instructions.On the earliest implementations (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] P5 Pentium, AMD K5), as well as on all processors that support x86-64, this MSR can be read and written as a full 64-bit register — however, on some non-x86-64 processors (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Fixed-rate TSC was introduced in two stages: *Constant TSC*TSC running at a fixed rate as long as the processor core is not in a deep-sleep (C2 or deeper) mode, but not synchronized between CPU cores.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Introduced in Intel Prescott, Yonah and Bonnell.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Also present in all Transmeta and VIA Nano CPUs, as well as AMD Geode LX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Does not have a CPUID bit.*Invariant TSC (Nonstop TSC)*TSC running at a fixed rate, and incrementing in a synchronized manner between all CPU cores in all P-,C- and T-states (but not necessarily S-states).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Present in AMD K10 and later; Intel Nehalem/Saltwell and later; Zhaoxin WuDaoKou and later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Indicated with a CPUID bit (leaf `8000_0007:EDX[8]`).On Intel processors, Intel guarantees that the time-stamp counter will not wraparound within 10 years of being reset.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `RDTSC` can be run outside Ring 0 only if `CR4.TSD=0`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On Intel Pentium and AMD K5/K6, `RDTSC` cannot be run in Virtual-8086 mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Later processors (Pentium Pro, Athlon 64) removed this restriction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `RDPMC` can be run outside Ring 0 only if `CR4.PCE=1`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `RDPMC` instruction is not present in VIA processors prior to the Nano.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] In 64-bit mode, `CMOVcc` with a 32-bit operand size will clear the upper 32 bits of the destination register even if the condition is false.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For `CMOVcc` with a memory source operand, the CPU will always read the operand from memory – potentially causing memory exceptions and cache line-fills – even if the condition for the move is not satisfied.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On pre-Nehemiah VIA C3 variants ("Samuel"/"Ezra"), the `reg,reg` but not `reg,[mem]` forms of the `CMOVcc` instructions have been reported to be present as undocumented instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Unlike other instructions added in Pentium Pro, long NOP does not have a CPUID feature bit.As of April 2026, the Intel SDM indicates that the long NOP is available on Family 6 and 15 CPUs — this holds for Intel CPUs, but some Family 6 CPUs from non-Intel vendors (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Cyrix 6x86MX and VIA C3) do not support it.The Linux kernel (version 2.6.27 and later) treats long NOP as unavailable in 32-bit mode due to a lack of a reliable way to detect it.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `0F 1F /0` as long-NOP was introduced in the Pentium Pro, but remained undocumented until 2006.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The whole `0F 18..1F` opcode range was `NOP` in Pentium Pro.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] However, except for `0F 1F /0`, Intel does not guarantee that these opcodes will remain `NOP` in future processors, and have indeed assigned some of these opcodes to other instructions in at least some processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] While the `0F 0B` opcode was officially reserved as an invalid opcode from Pentium onwards, it only got assigned the mnemonic `UD2` from Pentium Pro onwards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] GNU Binutils have used the `UD2A` and `UD2B` mnemonics for the `0F 0B` and `0F B9` opcodes since version 2.7.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Neither `UD2A` nor `UD2B` originally took any arguments - `UD2B` was later modified to accept a ModR/M byte, in Binutils version 2.30.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `UD2` (`0F 0B`) instruction will additionally stop subsequent bytes from being decoded as instructions, even speculatively.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For this reason, if an indirect branch instruction is followed by something that is not code, it is recommended to place an `UD2` instruction after the indirect branch.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The UD0/1/2 opcodes - `0F 0B`, `0F B9` and `0F FF` - will cause an #UD exception on all x86 processors from the 80186 onwards (except NEC V-series processors), but did not get explicitly reserved for this purpose until P5-class processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] While the `0F B9` opcode was officially reserved as an invalid opcode from Pentium onwards, it only got assigned its mnemonic `UD1` much later – AMD APM started listing `UD1` in its opcode maps from rev 3.17 onwards, while Intel SDM started listing it from rev 061 onwards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For both the `0F B9` and `0F FF` opcodes, different x86 implementations are known to differ regarding whether the opcodes accept a ModR/M byte.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For the `0F FF` opcode, the `OIO` mnemonic was introduced by Cyrix, while the `UD0` menmonic (without arguments) was introduced by AMD and Intel at the same time as the `UD1` mnemonic for `0F B9`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Later Intel (but not AMD) documentation modified its description of `UD0` to add a ModR/M byte and take two arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `SYSRET`, `SYSENTER` and `SYSEXIT` instructions are unavailable in Real mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `SYSENTER` is, however, available in Virtual 8086 mode.On AMD processors, the `SYSCALL` instruction is available in all operating modes, including Real Mode.If FRED (Flexible Return and Event Delivery) is enabled, then the `SYSRET` and `SYSEXIT` instructions are unavailable.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On K6, the `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` instructions were available on Model 7 (250nm "Little Foot") and later, not on the earlier Model 6.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `SYSCALL` and `SYSRET` were made an integral part of x86-64 – as a result, the instructions are available in 64-bit mode on all x86-64 processors from AMD, Intel, VIA and Zhaoxin.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Outside 64-bit mode, the instructions are available on AMD processors only.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The exact semantics of `SYSRET` differs slightly between AMD and Intel processors: non-canonical return addresses cause a #GP exception to be thrown in Ring 3 on AMD CPUs but Ring 0 on Intel CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] This has been known to cause security issues.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For the `SYSRET` and `SYSEXIT` instructions under x86-64, it is necessary to add the `REX.W` prefix for variants that will return to 64-bit user-mode code.Encodings of these instructions without the `REX.W` prefix are used to return to 32-bit user-mode code.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] (Neither of these instructions can be used to return to 16-bit user-mode code — for return to 16-bit code, `IRET`/`IRETD`/`IRETQ` should be used.)For variants of the `SYSRET` and `SYSEXIT` instructions encoded with the `REX.W` prefix, some assemblers (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] FASM and GNU Binutils) support the mnemonics `SYSRETQ` and `SYSEXITQ`, however these mnemonics are not used in Intel/AMD documentation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `CPUID` flags that indicate support for `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` are set on the Pentium Pro, even though the processor does not officially support these instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Third party testing indicates that the opcodes are present on the Pentium Pro but too buggy to be usable.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On AMD CPUs, the `SYSENTER` and `SYSEXIT` instructions are not available in x86-64 long mode (#UD).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On Transmeta CPUs, the `SYSENTER` and `SYSEXIT` instructions are only available with version 4.2 or higher of the Transmeta Code Morphing software.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On Nehemiah, `SYSENTER` and `SYSEXIT` are available only on stepping 8 and later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] These instructions can only be encoded in 64 bit mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Most instructions with a 64 bit operand size encode this using a `REX.W` prefix; in the absence of the `REX.W` prefix, the corresponding instruction with 32 bit operand size is encoded.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] This mechanism also applies to most other instructions with 32 bit operand size.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] These are not listed here as they do not gain a new mnemonic in Intel syntax when used with a 64 bit operand size.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `CMPXCHG16B` instruction was absent from a few of the earliest Intel/AMD x86-64 processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On Intel processors, the instruction was missing from Xeon "Nocona" stepping D, but added in stepping E.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On AMD K8 family processors, it was added in stepping F, at the same time as DDR2 support was introduced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For this reason, `CMPXCHG16B` has its own CPUID flag, separate from the rest of x86-64.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] Encodings of `MOVSXD` without REX.W prefix are permitted but discouraged – such encodings behave identically to 16/32-bit `MOV` (`8B /r`).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `UDB` opcode - `D6` - will cause an #UD (invalid instruction) exception in 64-bit mode on all known x86-64 processors, but was only explicitly reserved for this purpose and assigned the `UDB` mnemonic in 2025.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `D6` opcode will cause #UD in 64-bit mode only - in 16-bit and 32-bit modes (legacy and compatibility), it will, on most x86 processors, execute as the `SALC` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For all of the VEX-encoded instructions defined by BMI1 and BMI2, the operand size may be 32 or 64 bits, controlled by the VEX.W bit – none of these instructions are available in 16-bit variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The VEX-encoded instructions are not available in Real Mode and Virtual-8086 mode - other than that, the bit manipulation instructions are available in all operating modes on supported CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `LZCNT` instruction will execute as `BSR` on systems that do not support the LZCNT or ABM extensions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `BSR` computes the index of the highest set bit in the source operand, producing a different result from `LZCNT` for most input values.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] The `TZCNT` instruction will execute as `BSF` on systems that do not support the BMI1 extension.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] `BSF` produces the same result as `TZCNT` for all input operand values except zero – for which `TZCNT` returns input operand size, but `BSF` produces undefined behavior (leaves destination unmodified on most modern CPUs).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] For `BEXTR`, the start position and length are not masked and can take values from 0 to 255.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] If the selected bits extend beyond the end of the `r/m` argument (which has the usual 32/64-bit operand size), then the out-of-bounds bits are read out as 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] On AMD processors before Zen 3, the `PEXT` and `PDEP` instructions are quite slow and exhibit data-dependent timing due to the use of a microcoded implementation (about 18 to 300 cycles, depending on the number of bits set in the mask argument).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p02] As a result, it is often faster to use other instruction sequences on these processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] Intel CET (Control-Flow Enforcement Technology) adds two distinct features to help protect against security exploits such as return-oriented programming: a shadow stack (CET_SS), and indirect branch tracking (CET_IBT).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] `ENDBR32` and `ENDBR64` act as NOPs on processors that don't support CET_IBT or where IBT is disabled.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] This prefix has the same encoding as the DS: segment override prefix – as of April 2022, Intel documentation does not appear to specify whether this prefix also retains its old segment-override function when used as a no-track prefix, nor does it provide an official mnemonic for this prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] This is done by defining a series of *state-components*, each with a size and offset within a given save area, and each corresponding to a subset of the state needed for one CPU extension or another.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] The `EAX=0Dh` CPUID leaf is used to provide information about which state-components the CPU supports and what their sizes/offsets are, so that the OS can reserve the proper amount of space and set the associated enable-bits.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] XSAVE was added in steppings E0/R0 of Penryn and is not available in earlier steppings.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] The presence of this functionality of `XGETBV` is indicated by CPUID.(EAX=0Dh,ECX=1):EAX[bit 2].
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] The `XSETBV` instruction will cause a mandatory #VMEXIT if executed under Intel VT-x virtualization.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p03] XSAVEC and XSAVES were added in revision v2 of Zhaoxin Shijidadao and are not available in revision v1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] All of the `PREFETCH*` instructions are hint instructions with effects only on performance, not program semantics.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Providing an invalid address (e.g. address of an unmapped page or a non-canonical address) will cause the instruction to act as a NOP without any exceptions generated.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Intel processors, as well as AMD64 processors, the processor ignores the r/m field of the ModR/M byte for the `SFENCE`, `LFENCE` and `MFENCE` instructions — any value of x in the range 0..7 will result in a valid instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `SFENCE` instruction ensures that all memory stores after the `SFENCE` instruction are made globally observable after all memory stores before the `SFENCE`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] This imposes ordering on stores that can otherwise be reordered, such as non-temporal stores and stores to WC (Write-Combining) memory regions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Intel CPUs, as well as AMD CPUs from Zen1 onwards (but not older AMD CPUs), `SFENCE` also acts as a reordering barrier on cache flushes/writebacks performed with the `CLFLUSH`, `CLFLUSHOPT` and `CLWB` instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] (Older AMD CPUs require `MFENCE` to order `CLFLUSH`.) `SFENCE` is not ordered with respect to `LFENCE`, and an `SFENCE+LFENCE` sequence is not sufficient to prevent a load from being reordered past a previous store.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] To prevent such reordering, it is necessary to execute an `MFENCE`, `LOCK` or a serializing instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `LFENCE` instruction ensures that all memory loads after the `LFENCE` instruction are made globally observable after all memory loads before the `LFENCE`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The effect of dispatch-serialization is that `LFENCE` also acts as a speculation barrier and a reordering barrier for accesses to non-memory resources such as performance counters (accessed through e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On AMD CPUs, `LFENCE` is not necessarily dispatch-serializing by default – however, on all AMD CPUs that support any form of non-dispatch-serializing `LFENCE`, it can be made dispatch-serializing by setting bit 1 of MSR `C001_1029`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `MFENCE` instruction ensures that all memory loads, stores and cacheline-flushes after the `MFENCE` instruction are made globally observable after all memory loads, stores and cacheline-flushes before the `MFENCE`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Intel CPUs, `MFENCE` is *not* dispatch-serializing, and therefore cannot be used on its own to enforce ordering on accesses to non-memory resources such as performance counters and x2apic MSRs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `MFENCE` is still ordered with respect to `LFENCE`, so if there is a need to enforce ordering between memory stores and subsequent non-memory accesses, then such an ordering can be obtained by issuing an `MFENCE` followed by an `LFENCE`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The operation of the `PAUSE` instruction in 64-bit mode is, unlike `NOP`, unaffected by the presence of the `REX.R` prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Neither `NOP` nor `PAUSE` are affected by the other bits of the `REX` prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The actual length of the pause performed by the `PAUSE` instruction is implementation-dependent.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On systems without SSE2, `PAUSE` will execute as NOP.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Under VT-x or AMD-V virtualization, executing `PAUSE` many times in a short time interval may cause a #VMEXIT.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The number of `PAUSE` executions and interval length that can trigger #VMEXIT are platform-specific.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] While the `CLFLUSH` instruction was introduced together with SSE2, it has its own CPUID flag and may be present on processors not otherwise implementing SSE2 and/or absent from processors that otherwise implement SSE2.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] While the `MONITOR` and `MWAIT` instructions were introduced at the same time as SSE3, they have their own CPUID flag that needs to be checked separately from the SSE3 CPUID flag (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the `MONITOR` and `MWAIT` instructions, older Intel documentation lists instruction mnemonics with explicit operands (`MONITOR EAX,ECX,EDX` and `MWAIT EAX,ECX`), while newer documentation omits these operands.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Assemblers/disassemblers may support one or both of these variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `MONITOR`, the DS: segment can be overridden with a segment prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The memory area that will be monitored will be not just the single byte specified by DS:rAX, but a linear memory region containing the byte – the size and alignment of this memory region is implementation-dependent and can be queried through CPUID.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The memory location to monitor should have memory type WB (write-back cacheable), or else monitoring may fail.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] As of April 2024, no extensions or hints have been defined for the `MONITOR` instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] As such, the instruction requires ECX=0 and ignores EDX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On some processors, such as Intel Xeon Phi x200 and AMD K10 and later, there exist documented MSRs that can be used to enable `MONITOR` and `MWAIT` to run in Ring 3.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The wait performed by `MWAIT`may be ended by system events other than a memory write (e.g. cacheline evictions, interrupts) – the exact set of events that can cause the wait to end is implementation-specific.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Regardless of whether the wait was ended by a memory write or some other event, monitoring will have ended and it will be necessary to set up monitoring again with `MONITOR` before using `MWAIT` to wait for memory writes again.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The extension flags available for `MWAIT` in the ECX register are: BitsMWAIT Extension 0Treat interrupts as break events, even when masked (EFLAGS.IF=0).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] (Available on all non-NetBurst implementations of `MWAIT`.) 1Timed MWAIT: end the wait when the TSC reaches or exceeds the value in EDX:EBX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] (Undocumented, reportedly present in Intel Skylake and later Intel processors) 2Monitorless MWAIT 31:3Not used, must be set to zero.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The hint flags available for `MWAIT` in the EAX register are: BitsMWAIT Hint 3:0Sub-state within a C-state (see bits 7:4) (Intel processors only) 7:4Target CPU power C-state during wait, minus 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The C-states are processor-specific power states, which do not necessarily correspond 1:1 to ACPI C-states.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the `GETSEC` instruction, the `REX.W` prefix enables 64-bit addresses for the EXITAC leaf function only - REX prefixes are otherwise permitted but ignored for the instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `GETSEC`, most leaf functions are restricted to Ring 0, but the CAPABILITIES (EAX=0) and PARAMETERS (EAX=6) leaf functions are available in Ring 3.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The "core ID" value read by `RDTSCP` and `RDPID` is actually the `TSC_AUX` MSR (MSR `C000_0103h`).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Whether this value actually corresponds to a processor ID is a matter of operating system convention.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Unlike the older `RDTSC` instruction, `RDTSCP` will delay the TSC read until all previous instructions have retired, guaranteeing ordering with respect to preceding memory loads (but not stores).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `RDTSCP` is not ordered with respect to subsequent instructions, though.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `RDTSCP` can be run outside Ring 0 only if `CR4.TSD=0`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Support for `RDTSCP` was added in stepping F of the AMD K8, and is not available on earlier steppings.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] While the `POPCNT` instruction was introduced at the same time as SSE4.2, it is not considered to be a part of SSE4.2, but instead a separate extension with its own CPUID flag.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On AMD processors, it is considered to be a part of the ABM extension, but still has its own CPUID flag.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the `MOVBE` instruction, encodings that use both the `66h` prefix and the `REX.W` prefix will cause #UD on some processors (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Haswell) and should therefore be avoided.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Unlike the older `INVLPG` instruction, `INVPCID` will cause a #GP exception if the provided memory address is non-canonical.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] This discrepancy has been known to cause security issues.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `PREFETCH` and `PREFETCHW` instructions are mandatory parts of the 3DNow! instruction set extension, but are also available as a standalone extension on systems that do not support 3DNow!
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The opcodes for `PREFETCH` and `PREFETCHW` (`0F 0D /r`) execute as NOPs on Intel CPUs from Cedar Mill (65nm Pentium 4) onwards, with `PREFETCHW` gaining prefetch functionality from Broadwell onwards.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `PREFETCH` (`0F 0D /0`) instruction is a 3DNow! instruction, present on all processors with 3DNow! but not necessarily on processors with the PREFETCHW extension.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On AMD CPUs with PREFETCHW, opcode `0F 0D /0` as well as opcodes `0F 0D /2../7` are all documented to be performing prefetch.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Intel processors with PREFETCHW, these opcodes are documented as performing reserved-NOPs (except `0F 0D /2` being `PREFETCHWT1 m8` on Xeon Phi only) – third party testing indicates that some or all of these opcodes may be performing prefetch on at least some Intel Core CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The SMAP, PKU and RDPID instruction set extensions are supported on stepping 2 and later of Zhaoxin LuJiaZui, but not on earlier steppings.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Unlike the older `RDTSCP` instruction which can also be used to read the processor ID, user-mode `RDPID` is not disabled by `CR4.TSD=1`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `MOVDIR64`, the destination address given by ES:reg must be 64-byte aligned.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The operand size for the register argument is given by the address size, which may be overridden by the `67h` prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The 64-byte memory source argument does not need to be 64-byte aligned, and is not guaranteed to be read atomically.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `WBNOINVD` instruction will execute as `WBINVD` if run on a system that doesn't support the WBNOINVD extension.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `WBINVD` differs from `WBNOINVD` in that `WBINVD` will invalidate all cache lines after writeback.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] In initial implementations, the `PREFETCHIT0` and `PREFETCHIT1` instructions will perform code prefetch only when using the RIP-relative addressing mode and act as NOPs otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The PREFETCHI instructions are hint instructions only - if an attempt is made to prefetch an invalid address, the instructions will act as NOPs with no exceptions generated.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On processors that support Long-NOP but do not support the PREFETCHI instructions, these instructions will always act as NOPs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On processors that don't support branch hints, these prefixes are accepted but ignored when used with `Jcc`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Branch hints are supported on all NetBurst (Pentium 4 family) processors - but not supported on any other known processor prior to their re-introduction in "Redwood Cove" CPUs, starting with "Meteor Lake" in 2023.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] SGX is deprecated on desktop/laptop processors from 11th generation (Rocket Lake, Tiger Lake) onwards, but continues to be available on Xeon-branded server parts.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Intel documentation lists Ice Lake-SP and Tremont as the processors in which SGX oversubscription was introduced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] However, as of February 2026, no Ice Lake-SP or Tremont variants have been observed to have the SGX oversubscription extension CPUID feature bits set, while several have them cleared — the only processors to have been observed to have these feature bits set are some Ice Lake-U variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `EENTER` and `ERESUME` functions cannot be executed inside an SGX enclave – the other functions can only be executed inside an enclave.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `ENCLU` can only be executed in ring 3, not rings 0/1/2.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The leaf functions defined for `ENCLV` (selected by EAX) are: EAXFunction Added with OVERSUB 0 (EDECVIRTCHILD)Decrement VIRTCHILDCNT in SECS 1 (EINCVIRTCHILD)Increment VIRTCHILDCNT in SECS 2 (ESETCONTEXT)Set ENCLAVECONTEXT field in SECS Any unsupported value in EAX causes a #GP exception.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `ENCLV` instruction is only present on systems that support the EPC Oversubscription Extensions to SGX ("OVERSUB").
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `ENCLV` is only available if Intel VMX operation is enabled with `VMXON`, and will produce #UD otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `PTWRITE`, the write to the Processor Trace Packet will only happen if a set of enable-bits (the "TriggerEn", "ContextEn", "FilterEn" bits of the `RTIT_STATUS` MSR and the "PTWEn" bit of the `RTIT_CTL` MSR) are all set to 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `PTWRITE` instruction is indicated in the SDM to cause an #UD exception if the 66h instruction prefix is used, regardless of other prefixes.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The leaf functions defined for `PCONFIG` (selected by EAX) are: EAXFunction 0MKTME_KEY_PROGRAM: Program key and encryption mode to use with an TME-MK Key ID.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Added with TSE 1TSE_KEY_PROGRAM: Direct key programming for TSE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] 2TSE_KEY_PROGRAM_WRAPPED: Wrapped key programming for TSE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Any unsupported value in EAX causes a #GP(0) exception.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `CLDEMOTE`, the cache level that it will demote a cache line to is implementation-dependent.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Since the instruction is considered a hint, it will execute as a NOP without any exceptions if the provided memory address is invalid or not in the L1 cache.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] It may also execute as a NOP under other implementation-dependent circumstances as well.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On systems that do not support the CLDEMOTE extension, it executes as a NOP.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Intel documentation lists Tremont and Alder Lake as the processors in which CLDEMOTE was introduced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] However, as of May 2022, no Tremont or Alder Lake models have been observed to have the CPUID feature bit for CLDEMOTE set, while several of them have the CPUID bit cleared.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] As of April 2023, the CPUID feature bit for CLDEMOTE has been observed to be set for Sapphire Rapids.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `UMONITOR`, the operand size of the address argument is given by the address size, which may be overridden by the `67h` prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The default segment used is DS:, which can be overridden with a segment prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the `UMWAIT` and `TPAUSE` instructions, the operating system can use the `IA32_UMWAIT_CONTROL` MSR to limit the maximum amount of time that a single `UMWAIT`/`TPAUSE` invocation is permitted to wait.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `UMWAIT` and `TPAUSE` instructions will set `RFLAGS.CF` to 1 if they reached the `IA32_UMWAIT_CONTROL`-defined time limit and 0 otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `TPAUSE` and `UMWAIT` can be run outside Ring 0 only if `CR4.TSD=0`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the register argument to the `UMWAIT` and `TPAUSE` instructions, the following flag bits are supported: BitsUsage 0Preferred optimization state.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] While serialization can be performed with older instructions such as e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] `CPUID` and `IRET`, these instructions perform additional functions, causing side-effects and reduced performance when stand-alone instruction serialization is needed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] (`CPUID` additionally has the issue that it causes a mandatory #VMEXIT when executed under virtualization, which causes a very large overhead.) The `SERIALIZE` instruction performs serialization only, avoiding these added costs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] A bitmap of CPU history components that can be reset through `HRESET` is provided by CPUID.(EAX=20h,ECX=0):EBX.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `IBHF` instruction is only effective in Ring 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Executing the `IBHF` instruction in rings 1/2/3 is permitted, but will execute as a `NOP` with no branch history fence functionality.On processors that don't support IBHF, the instruction will execute as `NOP` regardless of ring.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `IBHF` instruction was added to Alder Lake and later Intel processors with a microcode update in May 2025.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Sapphire Rapids processors, the `UIRET` instruction always sets UIF (User Interrupt Flag) to 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] On Sierra Forest and later processors, `UIRET` will set UIF to the value of bit 1 of the value popped off the stack for RFLAGS - this functionality is indicated by `CPUID.(EAX=7,ECX=1):EDX[17]`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `ENQCMD` and `EMQCMDS`, the operand-size of the register argument is given by the current address-size, which can be overridden with the `67h` prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For the `RDMSRLIST` and `WRMSRLIST` instructions, the addresses specified in the RSI and RDI registers must be 8-byte aligned.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Even though the `CMPccXADD` instructions perform a locked memory operation, they do not require or accept the `LOCK` (`F0h`) prefix - attempting to use this prefix results in #UD.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Like other variants of MOV to/from the CRx registers, the AltMovCr8 encodings ignore the top 2 bits of the instruction's ModR/M byte, and always execute as if these two bits are set to `11b`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The AltMovCr8 encodings are available in 64-bit mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] However, combining the `LOCK` prefix with the `REX.R` prefix is not permitted and will cause an #UD exception.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] Support for AltMovCR8 was added in stepping F of the AMD K8, and is not available on earlier steppings.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] For `CLZERO`, the address size and 67h prefix control whether to use AX, EAX or RAX as address.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The default segment DS: can be overridden by a segment-override prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The provided address does not need to be aligned – hardware will align it as necessary.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The `CLZERO` instruction is intended for recovery from otherwise-fatal Machine Check errors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] It is non-cacheable, cannot be used to allocate a cache line without a memory access, and should not be used for fast memory clears.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The register numbering used by `RDPRU` does not necessarily match that of `RDMSR`/`WRMSR`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] The registers supported by `RDPRU` as of December 2022 are: ECXRegister 0MPERF (MSR 0E7h: Maximum Performance Frequency Clock Count) 1APERF (MSR 0E8h: Actual Performance Frequency Clock Count) Unsupported values in ECX return 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p04] If `CR4.TSD=1`, then the `RDPRU` instruction can only run in ring 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The x87 coprocessor, if present, provides support for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Not all of the arithmetic instructions provided by x87 obey PC and RC.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For each non-waiting x87 instruction whose mnemonic begins with `FN`, there exists a pseudo-instruction that has the same mnemonic except without the N.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] These pseudo-instructions consist of a `WAIT` instruction (opcode `9B`) followed by the corresponding non-waiting x87 instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For example:`FNCLEX` is an instruction with the opcode `DB E2`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The corresponding pseudo-instruction `FCLEX` is then encoded as `**9B** DB E2`.`FNSAVE ES:[BX+6]` is an instruction with the opcode `26 DD 77 06`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The data registers are marked as Empty but not otherwise modified.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On 80387 and earlier FPUs, if an `FNINIT` instruction is issued before a previous memory-referencing x87 instruction has completed, then any memory bus cycles associated with that previous x87 instruction may be aborted.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For detection of x87 coprocessors on systems that don't support `CPUID`, it is common to issue an `FNINIT` followed by an `FNSTCW` or `FNSTSW` and then check that the `FNSTCW`/`FNSTSW` wrote the expected value to memory.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On the 8087, such a detection procedure requires at least two intervening integer instructions between the `FNINIT` and the following `FNSTCW`/`FNSTSW` to work correctly.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `F(N)STSW` with the AX register as a destination is available on 80287 and later, but not on the 8087.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On 80387 and later x87 FPUs, `FLDENV`, `F(N)STENV`, `FRSTOR` and `F(N)SAVE` exist in 16-bit and 32-bit variants.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The 16-bit variants will load/store a 14-byte floating-point environment data structure to/from memory – the 32-bit variants will load/store a 28-byte data structure instead.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] (`F(N)SAVE`/`FRSTOR` will additionally load/store an additional 80 bytes of FPU data register content after the FPU environment, for a total of 94 or 108 bytes).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The choice between the 16-bit and 32-bit variants is based on the `CS.D` bit and the presence of the `66h` instruction prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On 8087 and 80287, only the 16-bit variants are available.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] 64-bit variants of these instructions do not exist – using `REX.W` under x86-64 will cause the 32-bit variants to be used.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Since these can only load/store the bottom 32 bits of FIP and FDP, it is recommended to use `FXSAVE64`/`FXRSTOR64` instead if 64-bit operation is desired.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] In the case of an x87 instruction producing an unmasked FPU exception, the 8087 FPU will signal an IRQ some indeterminate time after the instruction was issued.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This may not always be possible to handle, and so the FPU offers the `F(N)DISI` and `F(N)ENI` instructions to set/clear the Interrupt Mask bit (bit 7) of the x87 Control Word, to control the interrupt.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Later x87 FPUs, from 80287 onwards, changed the FPU exception mechanism to instead produce a CPU exception on the next x87 instruction.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This made the Interrupt Mask bit unnecessary, so it was removed.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] In later Intel x87 FPUs, the `F(N)ENI` and `F(N)DISI` instructions were kept for backwards compatibility, executing as NOPs that do not modify any x87 state.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `FST`/`FSTP` with an 80-bit destination (m80 or st(i)) and an sNaN source value is documented to produce exceptions on AMD but not Intel FPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `FSTP ST(0)` is a commonly used idiom for popping a single register off the x87 register stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On the Intel 8087 coprocessor, several reserved opcodes would perform operations behaving similarly to existing defined x87 instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] These opcodes were documented for the 8087 and 80287, but then omitted from later manuals until the October 2017 update of the Intel SDM.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] They are present on all known Intel x87 FPUs but unavailable on some older non-Intel FPUs, such as AMD Geode GX/LX, DM&P Vortex86 and NexGen 586PF.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On the 8087 and 80287, `FBSTP` and the load-constant instructions always use the round-to-nearest rounding mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On the 80387 and later x87 FPUs, these instructions will use the rounding mode specified in the x87 RC register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For the `FADDP`, `FSUBP`, `FSUBRP`, `FMULP`, `FDIVP`, `FDIVRP`, `FCOM`, `FCOMP` and `FXCH` instructions, x86 assemblers/disassemblers may recognize variants of the instructions with no arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Such variants are equivalent to variants using st(1) as their first argument.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On Intel Pentium and later processors, `FXCH` is implemented as a register renaming rather than a true data move.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This has no semantic effect, but enables zero-cycle-latency operation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] It also allows the instruction to break data dependencies for the x87 top-of-stack value, improving attainable performance for code optimized for these processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On Intel Pentium processors without MMX, the fastest way to copy data from system memory to uncached memory (such as video memory) was to use the m64 forms of `FILD` and `FISTP` in a loop.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This method has been used in some MS-DOS games such as Carmageddon and Pete Sampras Tennis '97.A recurring problem in x86 emulators that emulate the x87 FPU registers with a data-format that has less than 64 bits of mantissa precision (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] FP64 numbers, which have only 53 mantissa bits) is that when such `FILD`/`FISTP` loops are mapped to int64↔FP64 conversions, some low-order data bits of each 64-bit data item will be lost.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] In the case of e.g. framebuffer data, such data loss will show up as vertical stripes every 8 pixels.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For the `FIST` and `FISTP` instructions, if the top-of-stack value, after being rounded to integer, is too small or too large to be represented in the destination memory format, then the value stored to memory will *not* be clamped - instead, the x87 "Integer Indefinite" value will be stored.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This is a value that has the top bit set to 1 and all other bits set to 0.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `0x8000` for 16-bit integers.) The Integer Indefinite value will also be used if the top-of-stack value is Empty, NaN or ±∞.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The result of executing the `FBLD` instruction on non-BCD data is undefined.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For the `FBSTP` instruction, if the top-of-stack value is NaN or has a value that $10^{18}$ or greater after rounding, the x87 "BCD Indefinite" value will be stored.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On early Intel Pentium processors, floating-point divide was subject to the Pentium FDIV bug.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This also affected instructions that perform divide as part of their operations, such as `FPREM`, `FPTAN` and `FPATAN`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] If st(0) is ±∞, then on 8087/80287, an invalid-operation exception is raised and both M and E are set to NaN — on 80387 and later, M is set equal to st(0) and E is set to +∞ with no exception reported.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For `FPREM`, if the quotient Q is larger than $2^{63}$ , then the remainder calculation may have been done only partially – in this case, the `FPREM` instruction will need to be run again in order to complete the remainder calculation.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This is indicated by the instruction setting `C2` to 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] If the instruction did complete the remainder calculation, it will set `C2` to 0 and set the three bits `{C0,C3,C1}` to the bottom three bits of the quotient Q.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The remainder computation done by the `FPREM` instruction is always exact with no roundoff errors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Also, its absolute value must be either 0 or at least 1.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] If these requirements are not satisfied, the result is undefined.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] These restrictions were removed in the 80387.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For `FSCALE`, rounding is only applied in the case of overflow, underflow or subnormal result.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The x87 transcendental instructions do not obey PC or RC, but instead compute full 80-bit results.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] These results are not necessarily correctly rounded (see Table-maker's dilemma) – they may have an error of up to ±1 ulp on Pentium or later, or up to ±1.5 ulps on earlier x87 coprocessors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For the `FYL2X` and `FYL2XP1` instructions, the maximum error bound of ±1 ulp only holds for st(1)=1.0 – for other values of st(1), the error bound is increased to ±1.35 ulps.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `FYL2X` can produce a #Z (divide-by-zero exception) if st(0)=0 and st(1) is a finite nonzero value.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For `FPATAN`, the following adjustments are done as compared to just computing a one-argument arctangent of the ratio ${\frac {st(1)}{st(0)}}$ :If both st(0) and st(1) are ±∞, then the arctangent is computed as if each of st(0) and st(1) had been replaced with ±1 of the same sign.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] While `FNOP` is a no-op in the sense that will leave the x87 FPU register stack unmodified, it may still modify FIP and CC, and it may fault if a pending x87 FPU exception is present.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On Pentium and later processors, this requirement was removed for `F(N)SAVE` as well.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] If the top-of-stack register st(0) is Empty, then the `FSTPNCE` instruction will behave like `FINCSTP`, incrementing the stack pointer with no data movement and no exceptions reported.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Not including discontinued instructions specific to particular 80387-compatible FPU models.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] For the `FUCOM` and `FUCOMP` instructions, x86 assemblers/disassemblers may recognize variants of the instructions with no arguments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The 80387 `FPREM1` instruction differs from the older `FPREM` (`D9 F8`) instruction in that the quotient Q is rounded to integer with round-to-nearest-even rounding rather than the round-to-zero rounding used by `FPREM`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Like `FPREM`, `FPREM1` always computes an exact result with no roundoff errors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Like `FPREM`, it may also perform a partial computation if the quotient is too large, in which case it must be run again.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] If st(0) is finite and its absolute value is $2^{63}$ or greater, then the top-of-stack value st(0) is left unmodified and C2 is set, with no exception raised.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This applies to the `FSIN`, `FCOS` and `FSINCOS` instructions, as well as `FPTAN` on 80387 and later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] In this case, the `FSINCOS` and `FPTAN` instructions will also abstain from pushing a value onto the x87 register-stack.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The `FCOMI`, `FCOMIP`, `FUCOMI` and `FUCOMIP` instructions write their results to the `ZF`, `CF` and `PF` bits of the `EFLAGS` register.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] On Intel but not AMD processors, the `SF`, `AF` and `OF` bits of `EFLAGS` are also zeroed out by these instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The `FXSAVE` and `FXRSTOR` instructions were added in the "Deschutes" revision of Pentium II, and are not present in earlier "Klamath" revision.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] They are also considered an integral part of SSE and are therefore present in all processors with SSE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The `FXSAVE` and `FXRSTOR` instructions will save/restore SSE state only on processors that support SSE.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Otherwise, they will only save/restore x87 and MMX state.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The x87 section of the state saved/restored by `FXSAVE(64)`/`FXRSTOR(64)` has a completely different layout than the data structure of the older `F(N)SAVE`/`FRSTOR` instructions, enabling faster save/restore by avoiding misaligned loads and stores.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `FXSAVE` and `FXRSTOR` require their memory argument to be 16-byte aligned.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] When floating-point emulation is enabled with `CR0.EM=1`, `FXSAVE(64)` and `FXRSTOR(64)` are considered to be x87 instructions and will accordingly produce an #NM (device-not-available) exception.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Other than `WAIT`, these are the only opcodes outside the `D8..DF` ESC opcode space that exhibit this behavior.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Except on Netburst (Pentium 4 family) CPUs, all opcodes in `D8..DF` will produce #NM if `CR0.EM=1`, even for undefined opcodes that would produce #UD otherwise.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Unlike the older `F(N)SAVE` instruction, `FXSAVE` will not initialize the FPU after saving its state to memory, but instead leave the x87 coprocessor state unmodified.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The `FXSAVE64`/`FXRSTOR64` instruction differ from the `FXSAVE`/`FXRSTOR` instructions in that: `FXSAVE`/`FXRSTOR` will save/restore FIP and FDP as 32-bit items, and will also save/restore FCS and FDS as 16-bit items.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] `FXSAVE64`/`FXRSTOR64` will save/restore FIP and FDP as 64-bit items while not saving/restoring FCS and FDS.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This difference also applies to the later `XSAVE`/`XRSTOR` vs `XSAVE64`/`XRSTOR64` instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] As a result, saving both FCS/FDS and the top 32 bits of 64-bit FIP/FDP cannot be accomplished with 1 instruction, but instead requires running both `(F)XSAVE` and `(F)XSAVE64`.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] This has been known to cause problems, especially for 64-bit hypervisors running 16/32-bit guests.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The `FISTTP` instruction will, like the older `FIST` and `FISTP` instructions, store the x87 "Integer Indefinite" value if the top-of-stack value is too small/large to be represented in the memory destination format.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] x86 also includes discontinued instruction sets which are no longer supported by Intel and AMD, and undocumented instructions which execute but are not officially documented.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] The x86 CPUs contain undocumented instructions which are implemented on the chips but not listed in some official documents.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-instruction-listings-p05] Some of these instructions are widely available across many/most x86 CPUs, while others are specific to a narrow range of CPUs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The term is not synonymous with IBM PC compatibility, as this implies a multitude of other computer hardware.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Embedded systems and general-purpose computers used x86 chips before the PC-compatible market started, some of them before the IBM PC (1981) debut.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] As of June 2022, most desktop and laptop computers sold are based on the x86 architecture family, while mobile categories such as smartphones or tablets are dominated by ARM.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] At the high end, x86 continues to dominate computation-intensive workstation and cloud computing segments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] In the 1980s and early 1990s, when the 8088 and 80286 were still in common use, the term x86 usually represented any 8086-compatible CPU.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Today, however, x86 usually implies binary compatibility with the 32-bit instruction set of the 80386.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] This is due to the fact that this instruction set has become something of a lowest common denominator for many modern operating systems and also probably because the term became common after the introduction of the 80386 in 1985.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] A few years after the introduction of the 8086 and 8088, Intel added some complexity to its naming scheme and terminology as the "iAPX" of the ambitious but ill-fated Intel iAPX 432 processor was tried on the more successful 8086 family of chips, applied as a kind of system-level prefix.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] An 8086 system, including coprocessors such as 8087 and 8089, and simpler Intel-specific system chips, was thereby described as an iAPX 86 system.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] There were also terms *iRMX* (for operating systems), *iSBC* (for single-board computers), and *iSBX* (for multimodule boards based on the 8086 architecture), all together under the heading *Microsystem 80*.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] However, this naming scheme was quite temporary, lasting for a few years during the early 1980s.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Although the 8086 was primarily developed for embedded systems and small multi-user or single-user computers, largely as a response to the successful 8080-compatible Zilog Z80, the x86 line soon grew in features and processing power.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Today, x86 is ubiquitous in both stationary and portable personal computers, and is also used in video game consoles, midrange computers, workstations, servers, and most new supercomputer clusters of the TOP500 list.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] A large amount of software, including a large list of x86 operating systems are using x86-based hardware.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Modern x86 is relatively uncommon in embedded systems, however; small low power applications (using tiny batteries), and low-cost microprocessor markets, such as home appliances and toys, lack significant x86 presence.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Simple 8- and 16-bit based architectures are common here, as well as simpler RISC architectures like ARM and RISC-V, although the x86-compatible VIA C7, VIA Nano, AMD's Geode, Athlon Neo and Intel Atom are examples of 32- and 64-bit designs used in some relatively low-power and low-cost segments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] There have been several attempts, including by Intel, to end the market dominance of the "inelegant" x86 architecture designed directly from the first simple 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Examples of this are the iAPX 432 (a project originally named the *Intel 8800*), the Intel 960, Intel 860 and the Intel/Hewlett-Packard Itanium architecture.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] However, the continuous refinement of x86 microarchitectures, circuitry and semiconductor manufacturing would make it hard to replace x86 in many segments.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] For some advanced features, x86 may require a license from Intel, though some do not need it; x86-64 may require an additional license from AMD.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The table below lists processor models and model series implementing various architectures in the x86 family, in chronological order.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Each line item is characterized by significantly improved or commercially successful processor microarchitecture designs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] At various times, companies such as IBM, VIA, NEC, AMD, TI, STM, Fujitsu, OKI, Siemens, Cyrix, Intersil, C&T, NexGen, UMC, and DM&P started to design or manufacture x86 processors (CPUs) intended for personal computers and embedded systems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Other companies that designed or manufactured x86 or x87 processors include ITT Corporation, National Semiconductor, ULSI System Technology, and Weitek.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Such x86 implementations were seldom simple copies but often employed different internal microarchitectures and different solutions at the electronic and physical levels.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Quite naturally, early compatible microprocessors were 16-bit, while 32-bit designs were developed much later.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] For the personal computer market, real quantities started to appear around 1990 with i386 and i486 compatible processors, often named similarly to Intel's original chips.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] After the fully pipelined i486, in 1993 Intel introduced the Pentium brand name (which, unlike numbers, could be trademarked) for their new set of superscalar x86 designs.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Some early versions of these microprocessors had heat dissipation problems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The 6x86 was also affected by a few minor compatibility problems, the Nx586 lacked a floating-point unit (FPU) and (the then crucial) pin-compatibility, while the K5 had somewhat disappointing performance when it was (eventually) introduced.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Customer ignorance of alternatives to the Pentium series further contributed to these designs being comparatively unsuccessful, despite the fact that the K5 had very good Pentium compatibility and the 6x86 was significantly faster than the Pentium on integer code.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] AMD later managed to grow into a serious contender with the K6 set of processors, which gave way to the very successful Athlon and Opteron.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] There were also other contenders, such as Centaur Technology (formerly IDT), Rise Technology, and Transmeta.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] VIA Technologies' energy efficient C3 and C7 processors, which were designed by the Centaur company, were sold for many years following their release in 2005.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Centaur's 2008 design, the VIA Nano, was their first processor with superscalar and speculative execution.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] It was introduced at about the same time (in 2008) as Intel introduced the Intel Atom, its first "in-order" processor after the P5 Pentium.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Many additions and extensions have been added to the original x86 instruction set over the years, almost consistently with full backward compatibility.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The architecture family has been implemented in processors from Intel, Cyrix, AMD, VIA Technologies and many other companies; there are also open implementations, such as the Zet SoC platform (currently inactive).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Nevertheless, of those, only Intel, AMD, VIA Technologies, and DM&P Electronics hold x86 architectural licenses, and from these, only the first two actively produce modern 64-bit designs, leading to what has been called a "duopoly" of Intel and AMD in x86 processors.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] However, in 2014 the Shanghai-based Chinese company Zhaoxin, a joint venture between a Chinese company and VIA Technologies, began designing VIA based x86 processors for desktops and laptops.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The release of its newest "7" family of x86 processors (e.g.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] KX-7000), which are not quite as fast as AMD or Intel chips but are still state of the art, had been planned for 2021; as of March 2022 the release had not taken place, however.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The instruction set architecture has twice been extended to a larger word size.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] In 1999–2003, AMD extended this 32-bit architecture to 64 bits and referred to it as x86-64 in early documents and later as AMD64.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Intel soon adopted AMD's architectural extensions under the name IA-32e, later using the name EM64T and finally using Intel 64.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Microsoft and Sun Microsystems/Oracle also use term "x64", while many Linux distributions, and the BSDs also use the "amd64" term.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] Microsoft Windows, for example, designates its 32-bit versions as "x86" and 64-bit versions as "x64", while installation files of 64-bit Windows versions are required to be placed into a directory called "AMD64".
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] In 2023, Intel proposed a major change to the architecture referred to as X86S (formerly known as X86-S).
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The S in X86S stood for "simplification", which aimed to remove support for legacy execution modes and instructions.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] A processor implementing this proposal would have lacked support for legacy mode, started execution directly in long mode and provided a way to switch to 5-level paging without going through the unpaged mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The new architecture would have removed support for 16-bit and 32-bit operating systems.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] 32-bit code would have only been supported for user applications running in ring 3, and would have used the same simplified segmentation as long mode.
[src:x86-assembly/x86-p01] The draft specification received multiple updates, reaching version 1.2 by June 2024.
